const PRACTICE_POOL = [{"id":"phr01","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which plasma protein primarily binds midazolam in the canine patient?","options":["Globulin","Alpha-1-acid glycoprotein","Albumin","Fibrinogen"],"answer":2,"explain":"Midazolam, like most benzodiazepines and acidic/neutral drugs, is highly bound to albumin. Hypoalbuminemia increases the free (active) fraction, intensifying drug effect at a given dose."},{"id":"phr02","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Propofol causes apnea most commonly due to which factor?","options":["Rapid IV administration and dose","Concurrent opioid administration being the sole cause","An allergic reaction to the lipid emulsion vehicle","Direct laryngospasm from the injectate"],"answer":0,"explain":"Propofol-induced apnea is dose- and rate-dependent. Rapid bolus injection produces a high peak plasma concentration that depresses the central respiratory centers; titrating slowly to effect reduces this risk."},{"id":"phr03","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Alfaxalone produces anesthesia primarily by acting on which receptor?","options":["NMDA receptor antagonism","GABA-A receptor potentiation","Mu-opioid receptor agonism","Alpha-2 adrenergic agonism"],"answer":1,"explain":"Alfaxalone is a neuroactive steroid that potentiates GABA-A receptor activity, the major inhibitory neurotransmitter system, producing dose-dependent CNS depression."},{"id":"phr04","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Ketamine should be used cautiously or avoided in patients with which condition?","options":["Hypothyroidism","Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","Osteoarthritis","Well-controlled hypoadrenocorticism"],"answer":1,"explain":"Ketamine increases heart rate, myocardial oxygen demand, and sympathetic tone. In hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM) this worsens dynamic outflow obstruction and can precipitate decompensation."},{"id":"phr05","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which characteristic best describes etomidate's cardiovascular profile?","options":["Profound hypotension","Marked cardiovascular stability","Significant reflex tachycardia","Strong negative inotropy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Etomidate provides excellent cardiovascular stability with minimal effect on heart rate, contractility, or blood pressure, making it useful for cardiovascularly compromised patients. Its drawback is adrenocortical suppression."},{"id":"phr06","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Dexmedetomidine produces an initial increase in blood pressure followed by reflex bradycardia because of:","options":["Central alpha-1 stimulation","Peripheral alpha-2 mediated vasoconstriction","Beta-1 receptor blockade","Direct vagal nucleus inhibition"],"answer":1,"explain":"Initial peripheral alpha-2B receptor activation on vascular smooth muscle causes vasoconstriction and hypertension, triggering a baroreceptor-mediated reflex bradycardia. Later central alpha-2A effects lower sympathetic outflow."},{"id":"phr07","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"MAC (minimum alveolar concentration) is defined as the concentration that prevents movement in what percentage of patients to a noxious stimulus?","options":["25%","50%","75%","95%"],"answer":1,"explain":"MAC is the alveolar concentration of an inhalant that prevents gross purposeful movement in 50% of patients exposed to a supramaximal noxious stimulus. It is the standard measure of inhalant potency."},{"id":"phr08","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which of the following factors DECREASES MAC?","options":["Hyperthermia","Hypothermia","Young age","Hypernatremia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hypothermia decreases MAC (less anesthetic needed). Other MAC-reducing factors: opioids, alpha-2 agonists, pregnancy, hyponatremia, severe hypotension, and old age. Hyperthermia and youth increase MAC."},{"id":"phr09","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A lower blood-gas partition coefficient results in:","options":["Faster induction and recovery","Higher potency","A greater oil:gas partition coefficient","Slower induction but faster recovery"],"answer":0,"explain":"A low blood:gas partition coefficient (e.g., sevoflurane 0.65 vs isoflurane 1.4) means less anesthetic dissolves in blood, so alveolar partial pressure rises faster, producing more rapid induction and recovery."},{"id":"phr10","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which inhalant is most associated with potential nephrotoxicity from Compound A production with low fresh gas flows?","options":["Isoflurane","Sevoflurane","Desflurane","Nitrous oxide"],"answer":1,"explain":"Sevoflurane degrades to Compound A when in contact with desiccated CO2 absorbents at low fresh gas flow. While clinically rare in veterinary patients, maintaining adequate flows is recommended."},{"id":"phr11","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which opioid is a partial mu-agonist with a ceiling effect and high receptor affinity, making it difficult to reverse?","options":["Hydromorphone","Fentanyl","Buprenorphine","Methadone"],"answer":2,"explain":"Buprenorphine is a partial mu-agonist with very high receptor affinity and slow dissociation, giving a long duration but a ceiling effect and resistance to naloxone reversal (requiring higher/repeated naloxone doses)."},{"id":"phr12","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Methadone offers an analgesic advantage over pure mu-agonists like hydromorphone because it also:","options":["Antagonizes GABA receptors","Acts as an NMDA receptor antagonist","Blocks alpha-2 receptors","Inhibits cyclooxygenase"],"answer":1,"explain":"In addition to mu-agonism, methadone antagonizes NMDA receptors and inhibits monoamine reuptake, which may provide enhanced analgesia and reduce central sensitization/wind-up."},{"id":"phr13","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Naloxone is administered to a patient that received hydromorphone. The technician should anticipate:","options":["Reversal of both analgesia and respiratory depression","Selective reversal of respiratory depression only, preserving analgesia","Reversal of sedation while analgesia continues","Reversal of nausea without affecting analgesia"],"answer":0,"explain":"Naloxone is a pure opioid antagonist that reverses ALL opioid effects, including the desired analgesia. Titrate slowly to restore ventilation while preserving as much analgesia as possible; re-dosing may be needed (short half-life)."},{"id":"phr14","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which receptor is responsible for the analgesic and respiratory depressant effects of opioids?","options":["Kappa","Delta","Mu","Sigma"],"answer":2,"explain":"The mu-opioid receptor mediates the most potent analgesia but also respiratory depression, euphoria/dysphoria, bradycardia, and GI effects. Kappa provides milder analgesia with less respiratory depression."},{"id":"phr15","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Atropine is preferred over glycopyrrolate in an acute bradycardic crisis because atropine:","options":["Has a longer duration of action","Crosses the blood-brain barrier and is longer-lasting","Has a faster onset of action","Does not cross the placenta"],"answer":2,"explain":"Atropine has a faster onset than glycopyrrolate, making it preferable in acute symptomatic bradycardia. Glycopyrrolate has slower onset/longer duration and does not cross the blood-brain barrier or placenta."},{"id":"phr16","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Atipamezole is the reversal agent for which drug class?","options":["Opioids","Benzodiazepines","Alpha-2 agonists","Phenothiazines"],"answer":2,"explain":"Atipamezole is a specific alpha-2 antagonist used to reverse dexmedetomidine/medetomidine/xylazine. It should be given IM (not IV) to avoid acute hypotension and excitement."},{"id":"phr17","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Flumazenil reverses the effects of which drug?","options":["Ketamine","Midazolam","Acepromazine","Fentanyl"],"answer":1,"explain":"Flumazenil is a benzodiazepine antagonist that reverses midazolam and diazepam. It has a short duration, so re-sedation can occur if the benzodiazepine outlasts the flumazenil."},{"id":"phr18","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Acepromazine should be avoided in a hypotensive patient because it causes:","options":["Alpha-1 mediated vasodilation and hypotension","Beta-2 mediated vasodilation","Histamine release causing vasodilation","Direct myocardial depression reducing output"],"answer":0,"explain":"Acepromazine is a phenothiazine that blocks peripheral alpha-1 receptors, causing vasodilation and a drop in blood pressure. It is contraindicated in hypovolemic, hypotensive, or shock patients."},{"id":"phy01","domain":"Physiology","q":"During phase 0 (depolarization) of the cardiac myocyte action potential, which ion movement occurs?","options":["Chloride channels open","Potassium channels open","Calcium channels open","Sodium channels open"],"answer":3,"explain":"Phase 0 (rapid depolarization) of the fast cardiac action potential is driven by the rapid opening of fast voltage-gated sodium channels, causing a steep upstroke. Calcium enters during the plateau (phase 2)."},{"id":"phy02","domain":"Physiology","q":"Cardiac output is the product of heart rate and which other variable?","options":["Systemic vascular resistance","Stroke volume","Mean arterial pressure","Central venous pressure"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cardiac output (CO) = heart rate × stroke volume. Stroke volume is determined by preload, afterload, and contractility. Understanding this guides interventions for hypotension under anesthesia."},{"id":"phy03","domain":"Physiology","q":"Mean arterial pressure (MAP) is calculated as:","options":["Systolic minus diastolic","Diastolic + 1/3(systolic − diastolic)","Systolic + 1/3(diastolic)","(Systolic + diastolic) / 2 only"],"answer":1,"explain":"MAP ≈ diastolic pressure + 1/3 of the pulse pressure (systolic − diastolic). This reflects that the heart spends roughly two-thirds of the cycle in diastole. MAP ≥ 60 mmHg is the usual minimum for organ perfusion."},{"id":"phy04","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which compensatory mechanism maintains arterial blood pressure when cardiac output falls?","options":["Baroreceptor-mediated bradycardia","Baroreceptor-mediated vasoconstriction","Atrial natriuretic peptide release","Increased vagal tone to the SA node"],"answer":1,"explain":"Baroreceptors in the carotid sinus and aortic arch detect a fall in pressure and trigger increased sympathetic outflow, causing vasoconstriction (increased SVR) and tachycardia to restore blood pressure."},{"id":"phy05","domain":"Physiology","q":"The primary stimulus to breathe in a healthy anesthetized patient is:","options":["Low arterial oxygen (PaO2)","Elevated arterial carbon dioxide (PaCO2)","Low blood pH alone","Lung stretch receptor activation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Central chemoreceptors respond primarily to rising PaCO2 (via CSF pH). The hypoxic drive (peripheral chemoreceptors responding to low PaO2) is a secondary, weaker stimulus that becomes important only in chronic CO2 retainers."},{"id":"phy06","domain":"Physiology","q":"A patient with an ETCO2 of 65 mmHg is experiencing:","options":["Hypocapnia","Normocapnia","Hypercapnia","Respiratory alkalosis"],"answer":2,"explain":"Normal ETCO2 is roughly 35–45 mmHg. A value of 65 mmHg indicates hypercapnia (hypoventilation), commonly from anesthetic-induced respiratory depression. Management includes assisted/controlled ventilation."},{"id":"phy07","domain":"Physiology","q":"The oxyhemoglobin dissociation curve shifts to the RIGHT (offloading more O2 to tissues) with:","options":["Alkalosis and hypothermia","Acidosis, hypercarbia, and increased temperature","Decreased 2,3-DPG","Hypocapnia"],"answer":1,"explain":"A rightward shift (decreased Hb affinity, more O2 release to tissues) occurs with acidosis (Bohr effect), hypercarbia, hyperthermia, and increased 2,3-DPG. Leftward shifts occur with the opposite conditions."},{"id":"phy08","domain":"Physiology","q":"Hypoventilation under anesthesia leads to which acid-base disturbance?","options":["Respiratory alkalosis","Metabolic acidosis","Respiratory acidosis","Metabolic alkalosis"],"answer":2,"explain":"Hypoventilation causes CO2 retention. Increased PaCO2 lowers blood pH, producing respiratory acidosis. This is the most common acid-base disturbance during general anesthesia."},{"id":"phy09","domain":"Physiology","q":"What is the primary cause of decreased renal blood flow in geriatric patients under anesthesia?","options":["Reduction of ADH","Decrease in cardiac output","Aldosterone loss","Increased atrial natriuretic peptide release"],"answer":1,"explain":"Geriatric patients have reduced cardiovascular reserve and decreased cardiac output, which lowers renal perfusion. Maintaining blood pressure and cardiac output is essential to preserve renal blood flow and GFR."},{"id":"phy10","domain":"Physiology","q":"Why are anesthetic drug doses often reduced in patients with significant hepatic disease?","options":["Induction of hepatic cytochrome P450 enzymes","Reduced plasma protein production and impaired drug metabolism","Increased renal clearance","Enhanced biliary excretion"],"answer":1,"explain":"The liver produces albumin and metabolizes many anesthetic drugs. Hepatic disease reduces albumin (more free drug) and slows metabolism (prolonged effect), so doses should be reduced and titrated carefully."},{"id":"eq01","domain":"Equipment","q":"The primary function of the oxygen flush valve is to:","options":["Deliver anesthetic gas rapidly","Deliver high-flow oxygen bypassing the vaporizer","Rapidly increase the inspired anesthetic concentration","Supply the drive gas that powers the ventilator bellows"],"answer":1,"explain":"The O2 flush valve delivers a high flow of pure oxygen (35-75 L/min) directly to the common gas outlet, bypassing the vaporizer. It rapidly fills the breathing circuit WITHOUT anesthetic — never use with a closed pop-off and patient connected (barotrauma risk)."},{"id":"eq02","domain":"Equipment","q":"A non-rebreathing (e.g., Bain) circuit is most appropriate for a patient of which weight?","options":["Under 5-7 kg","10-15 kg","20-30 kg","Over 40 kg"],"answer":0,"explain":"Non-rebreathing systems are used for small patients (typically under 5-7 kg) because they have low resistance and minimal dead space/work of breathing, but they require high fresh gas flows and provide little heat/moisture conservation."},{"id":"eq03","domain":"Equipment","q":"The purpose of the CO2 absorbent (soda lime) in a rebreathing circuit is to:","options":["Absorb waste anesthetic agent before it is scavenged","Remove exhaled carbon dioxide","Filter bacteria and particulate matter from inspired gas","Vaporize the inhalant"],"answer":1,"explain":"Soda lime chemically neutralizes exhaled CO2, allowing exhaled gas (minus CO2) to be rebreathed. Exhausted absorbent (color change, hardening, lack of heat) leads to rebreathing of CO2 and hypercapnia."},{"id":"eq04","domain":"Equipment","q":"A precision vaporizer is described as 'out-of-circuit' meaning it is located:","options":["Inside the breathing circuit","On the fresh gas inlet, outside the breathing circuit","On the expiratory limb, downstream of the patient","Between the common gas outlet and the reservoir bag"],"answer":1,"explain":"A precision (out-of-circuit, VOC) vaporizer sits between the flowmeter and the common gas outlet, outside the breathing circuit. It is temperature, flow, and pressure compensated to deliver a precise concentration."},{"id":"eq05","domain":"Equipment","q":"During a machine leak check, the circuit is pressurized to 30 cmH2O. An acceptable system holds pressure with a leak rate less than:","options":["50 mL/min","100-300 mL/min","500-750 mL/min","1 L/min"],"answer":1,"explain":"A low-pressure leak test should show minimal pressure loss; generally a leak under ~300 mL/min (often cited as <100-300 mL/min) is acceptable. Larger leaks risk inadequate gas delivery and waste anesthetic gas/pollution."},{"id":"eq06","domain":"Equipment","q":"What is the most serious immediate risk of leaving the pop-off (APL) valve closed during spontaneous ventilation?","options":["Rebreathing of CO2 causing hypercapnia","Barotrauma and cardiovascular collapse","Progressive loss of anesthetic depth from gas dilution","Rapid emptying of the reservoir bag"],"answer":1,"explain":"A closed pop-off valve allows pressure to build in the circuit and lungs, causing barotrauma (pneumothorax/lung rupture), decreased venous return, and cardiovascular collapse. Always re-open after manual ventilation."},{"id":"mon01","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A pulse oximeter reading (SpO2) of 90% corresponds to an approximate PaO2 of:","options":["100 mmHg","80 mmHg","60 mmHg","40 mmHg"],"answer":2,"explain":"On the oxyhemoglobin dissociation curve, SpO2 90% corresponds to a PaO2 of roughly 60 mmHg — the threshold of hypoxemia. Below this, small drops in saturation reflect large drops in PaO2 (steep part of the curve)."},{"id":"mon02","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Capnography measures which parameter directly?","options":["Arterial oxygen","End-tidal carbon dioxide","Blood pH","Hemoglobin saturation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Capnography measures the CO2 concentration in expired gas (ETCO2), reflecting ventilation, circulation, and metabolism. A sudden loss of waveform can indicate esophageal intubation, circuit disconnect, or cardiac arrest."},{"id":"mon03","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A sudden drop of ETCO2 to near zero with a flat waveform most likely indicates:","options":["Gradual hyperventilation lowering the ETCO2","Esophageal intubation or circuit disconnection","Rebreathing from exhausted absorbent (raised baseline)","Bronchospasm producing a sloped expiratory plateau"],"answer":1,"explain":"A sudden loss of the capnograph waveform indicates no CO2 is reaching the sensor — causes include esophageal intubation, airway disconnection, ET tube obstruction, apnea, or cardiac arrest. Immediate assessment is required."},{"id":"mon04","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Doppler blood pressure monitoring in cats most reliably estimates which pressure?","options":["Diastolic pressure only","Central venous pressure","Systolic (or close to mean) pressure","Pulse pressure (systolic minus diastolic)"],"answer":2,"explain":"In cats, the Doppler-measured value tends to underestimate true systolic and is often considered closer to mean arterial pressure. It provides an audible, continuous pulse signal — valuable in small or hypotensive patients."},{"id":"mon05","domain":"Monitoring","q":"On an ECG, the QRS complex represents:","options":["Atrial depolarization","Ventricular depolarization","Ventricular repolarization","Atrial repolarization"],"answer":1,"explain":"The QRS complex represents ventricular depolarization. The P wave is atrial depolarization, and the T wave is ventricular repolarization. Recognizing wide/bizarre QRS complexes helps identify ventricular arrhythmias (VPCs)."},{"id":"mon06","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Which arrhythmia is characterized by wide, bizarre QRS complexes with no associated P wave?","options":["Sinus arrhythmia","Atrial premature complex","Ventricular premature complex (VPC)","First-degree AV block"],"answer":2,"explain":"VPCs arise from an ectopic ventricular focus, producing wide and bizarre QRS complexes not preceded by a P wave. Frequent VPCs, runs of V-tach, or R-on-T phenomena warrant treatment (e.g., lidocaine)."},{"id":"pn01","domain":"Pain Management","q":"'Multimodal analgesia' refers to:","options":["Escalating the dose of a single opioid until the patient is comfortable","Combining drugs from different classes acting at different points in the pain pathway","Alternating two opioids to prevent tolerance","Combining an opioid with a benzodiazepine for sedation and analgesia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Multimodal (balanced) analgesia combines agents acting at different sites of the nociceptive pathway (e.g., opioid + NSAID + local block + alpha-2), improving efficacy while lowering each drug's dose and side effects."},{"id":"pn02","domain":"Pain Management","q":"'Wind-up' (central sensitization) is best prevented by:","options":["Administering an NMDA antagonist only after surgery is finished","Pre-emptive analgesia before the noxious stimulus","Relying on a single intraoperative opioid bolus","Increasing the inhalant concentration whenever the patient moves"],"answer":1,"explain":"Wind-up is the amplification of pain signaling from repeated noxious input. Pre-emptive analgesia (treating BEFORE the stimulus) blunts NMDA-mediated central sensitization and reduces overall analgesic requirements."},{"id":"pn03","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Which class of drug should be avoided in a hypovolemic or hypotensive patient due to effects on renal blood flow?","options":["Opioids","NSAIDs","Local anesthetics","Benzodiazepines"],"answer":1,"explain":"NSAIDs inhibit prostaglandins that maintain renal blood flow during hypoperfusion. In hypovolemic, hypotensive, or dehydrated patients this can precipitate acute kidney injury, so NSAIDs are avoided until perfusion is restored."},{"id":"pn04","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A validated tool for assessing acute pain in dogs is the:","options":["Glasgow Composite Measure Pain Scale","Feline Grimace Scale","ASA Physical Status classification","Body condition score (BCS)"],"answer":0,"explain":"The Glasgow Composite Measure Pain Scale (and the Colorado State scales) are validated acute pain assessment tools. Objective, repeatable pain scoring guides analgesic decisions and is expected in AVTAA case documentation."},{"id":"loc01","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Which dental nerve block is appropriate for desensitizing a maxillary canine tooth (upper canine)?","options":["Mental block","Mandibular (inferior alveolar) block","Infraorbital block","Auriculotemporal block"],"answer":2,"explain":"The infraorbital block desensitizes the maxillary (upper) teeth rostral to the infraorbital foramen, including the upper canine and incisors. The mandibular block is for lower arcade teeth."},{"id":"loc02","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Which local anesthetic has the LONGEST duration of action?","options":["Lidocaine","Mepivacaine","Bupivacaine","Procaine"],"answer":2,"explain":"Bupivacaine has a long duration (4-6+ hours) due to high protein binding, versus lidocaine (1-2 hours). However, bupivacaine is more cardiotoxic and must NEVER be given IV."},{"id":"loc03","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Why must bupivacaine never be administered intravenously?","options":["It triggers an allergic reaction because it is an ester-type anesthetic","It is highly cardiotoxic and can cause refractory arrhythmias","It is broken down by plasma esterases and provides no block","It selectively blocks cardiac potassium channels, slowing conduction"],"answer":1,"explain":"Bupivacaine binds avidly to cardiac sodium channels; accidental IV injection can cause severe, refractory ventricular arrhythmias and cardiac arrest. Always aspirate before injecting local blocks."},{"id":"loc04","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"For a right TPLO (stifle) procedure, which two locoregional techniques are most appropriate?","options":["Infraorbital and mental blocks","Femoral and sciatic nerve blocks (or epidural)","Brachial plexus and RUMM blocks","Intercostal and interpleural blocks"],"answer":1,"explain":"The stifle is innervated by the femoral and sciatic nerves; blocking both (or performing a lumbosacral epidural) provides analgesia for TPLO. Brachial plexus/RUMM blocks are for the thoracic limb."},{"id":"loc05","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Early signs of local anesthetic systemic toxicity (LAST) include:","options":["Cardiac arrhythmias and hypotension as the very first sign","Muscle twitching, tremors, and seizures","Hypertension with reflex bradycardia","Excessive salivation, lacrimation, and miosis"],"answer":1,"explain":"LAST affects the CNS first (muscle twitching, tremors, seizures) before cardiovascular collapse. Lipid emulsion therapy is the treatment for severe (especially bupivacaine) toxicity. Always calculate and respect maximum doses."},{"id":"er01","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Per RECOVER guidelines, the chest compression rate during CPR should be:","options":["60-80 per minute","100-120 per minute","140-160 per minute","80-100 per minute"],"answer":1,"explain":"RECOVER guidelines recommend chest compressions at 100-120/min, compressing 1/3 to 1/2 the width of the chest, allowing full recoil, with minimal interruptions and rotating compressors every 2 minutes."},{"id":"er02","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"The first-line drug for asystole or pulseless electrical activity (PEA) during CPR is:","options":["Atropine","Epinephrine (low dose)","Lidocaine","Calcium gluconate"],"answer":1,"explain":"Low-dose epinephrine (0.01 mg/kg IV) every other BLS cycle is first-line for asystole/PEA. Atropine may be added for vagally-mediated arrest. High-dose epinephrine is reserved for prolonged CPR."},{"id":"er03","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"During CPR, ventilations should be delivered at a rate of approximately:","options":["6 breaths per minute","10 breaths per minute","30 breaths per minute","40 breaths per minute"],"answer":1,"explain":"RECOVER recommends ~10 breaths/min (one every 6 seconds) with an intubated patient, avoiding hyperventilation, which raises intrathoracic pressure and reduces venous return and coronary perfusion."},{"id":"er04","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"A rising ETCO2 during CPR is a positive sign because it indicates:","options":["The patient is hypoventilating","Effective chest compressions are restoring pulmonary blood flow","Sodium bicarbonate administration is taking effect","The endotracheal tube is dislodged"],"answer":1,"explain":"During CPR, ETCO2 reflects pulmonary blood flow generated by compressions. A rising ETCO2 (especially a sudden jump) suggests improved circulation and may signal return of spontaneous circulation (ROSC)."},{"id":"calc01","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 20 kg dog receives hydromorphone at 0.1 mg/kg. The concentration is 2 mg/mL. What volume is drawn up?","options":["0.5 mL","1.0 mL","2.0 mL","4.0 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dose = 20 kg × 0.1 mg/kg = 2 mg. Volume = 2 mg ÷ 2 mg/mL = 1.0 mL. Always double-check concentration and units before drawing up controlled drugs."},{"id":"calc02","domain":"Calculations","q":"A patient needs a fentanyl CRI at 5 mcg/kg/hr. The patient weighs 10 kg. How many mcg/hr are delivered?","options":["5 mcg/hr","25 mcg/hr","50 mcg/hr","100 mcg/hr"],"answer":2,"explain":"5 mcg/kg/hr × 10 kg = 50 mcg/hr. Verify whether your CRI is dosed per hour or per minute, and convert concentration (typically fentanyl is 50 mcg/mL) when setting the pump rate."},{"id":"calc03","domain":"Calculations","q":"What is the lidocaine dose in mg for a 25 kg dog given a bolus of 2 mg/kg?","options":["25 mg","50 mg","75 mg","100 mg"],"answer":1,"explain":"25 kg × 2 mg/kg = 50 mg. Lidocaine is a first-line antiarrhythmic for ventricular arrhythmias in dogs (use with extreme caution/avoid in cats due to toxicity)."},{"id":"calc04","domain":"Calculations","q":"A surgical maintenance fluid rate is commonly cited as approximately:","options":["1-2 mL/kg/hr","3-5 mL/kg/hr (with newer recommendations even lower)","10-20 mL/kg/hr","50 mL/kg/hr"],"answer":1,"explain":"Traditional anesthetic fluid rates were ~5-10 mL/kg/hr, but updated recommendations favor more conservative rates (~3-5 mL/kg/hr in dogs, ~3 in cats) to avoid volume overload, adjusting for losses and blood pressure."},{"id":"sp01","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Brachycephalic dogs require special attention during recovery primarily because of:","options":["Increased risk of upper airway obstruction","Rapid heat loss from a high surface-area-to-mass ratio","Prolonged recovery from redistribution-dependent injectable drugs","Increased risk of hypoglycemia from limited glycogen stores"],"answer":0,"explain":"Brachycephalic patients have stenotic nares, elongated soft palates, and everted saccules, predisposing them to upper airway obstruction. Keep them intubated as long as tolerated and monitor closely during recovery."},{"id":"sp02","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Cats are more prone to which complication during intubation compared to dogs?","options":["Esophageal perforation","Laryngospasm","Tracheal collapse","Bronchial intubation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cats have a highly sensitive larynx prone to laryngospasm. Desensitize with a drop of lidocaine on the arytenoids and intubate gently to avoid trauma and spasm."},{"id":"sp03","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Why are pediatric (neonatal) patients prone to hypoglycemia under anesthesia?","options":["Excessive insulin secretion from an immature pancreas","Immature hepatic glycogen stores and high metabolic rate","Reduced intestinal glucose absorption","A large fat reserve that suppresses gluconeogenesis"],"answer":1,"explain":"Neonates have limited hepatic glycogen reserves and a high metabolic rate, making them prone to hypoglycemia during fasting/anesthesia. Minimize fasting time and monitor blood glucose; supplement dextrose if needed."},{"id":"cx01","domain":"Complications","q":"The most common cause of hypotension under general inhalant anesthesia is:","options":["Excessive intravenous fluid administration","Anesthetic depth-related vasodilation and myocardial depression","Hyperventilation lowering arterial CO2","Peripheral vasoconstriction from hypothermia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Inhalant anesthetics cause dose-dependent vasodilation and myocardial depression. The first response to hypotension is usually to decrease the vaporizer setting (lighten anesthetic depth), then address fluids/inotropes."},{"id":"cx02","domain":"Complications","q":"A complication associated with intermittent positive pressure ventilation (IPPV) is:","options":["Decreased cardiac output","Reduced blood oxygen levels","Improved venous return to the heart","Increased lung compliance"],"answer":0,"explain":"IPPV increases intrathoracic pressure, which reduces venous return (preload) and can decrease cardiac output and blood pressure, especially in hypovolemic patients. Use the lowest effective airway pressure."},{"id":"cx03","domain":"Complications","q":"Malignant hyperthermia is a rare anesthetic emergency most classically triggered by:","options":["Propofol","Volatile inhalants and succinylcholine","Opioids","Benzodiazepines"],"answer":1,"explain":"Malignant hyperthermia is a hypermetabolic crisis (especially in susceptible pigs) triggered by volatile inhalants and succinylcholine, causing rapidly rising ETCO2, hyperthermia, and rigidity. Dantrolene is the treatment."},{"id":"cx04","domain":"Complications","q":"A patient becomes progressively bradycardic under a dexmedetomidine CRI with adequate blood pressure. The most appropriate first action is to:","options":["Immediately give atropine","Reduce or discontinue the dexmedetomidine and reassess","Give a fluid bolus","Increase the inhalant"],"answer":1,"explain":"Alpha-2 agonist bradycardia accompanies increased vascular resistance; giving anticholinergics into high afterload can cause hypertension and increased myocardial work. First reduce/stop the alpha-2 agonist and reassess before anticholinergics."},{"id":"vf01","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"Peak inspiratory pressure during manual or mechanical ventilation of a healthy small animal should generally not exceed:","options":["2-5 cmH2O","10-15 cmH2O (up to ~20)","20-25 cmH2O","30-40 cmH2O"],"answer":1,"explain":"Normal lungs are typically ventilated to a peak inspiratory pressure of ~10-15 cmH2O (some allow up to 20). Excessive pressure (especially >20-30) risks barotrauma/volutrauma. Higher pressures may be needed transiently for recruitment."},{"id":"vf02","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"A 5% dextrose in water (D5W) solution is best classified as a:","options":["Colloid","Hypertonic crystalloid","Replacement crystalloid","Free-water (maintenance-type) solution once dextrose is metabolized"],"answer":3,"explain":"D5W provides free water after the dextrose is metabolized; it is not a volume expander and does not stay in the vasculature. It is used for free-water deficits or as a dextrose vehicle, not for resuscitation."},{"id":"vf03","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"Which fluid is a synthetic colloid used to expand intravascular volume?","options":["0.9% NaCl","Lactated Ringer's solution","Hydroxyethyl starch (hetastarch)","D5W"],"answer":2,"explain":"Hydroxyethyl starch (hetastarch) is a synthetic colloid containing large molecules that remain in the vasculature longer, expanding plasma volume. Use cautiously due to coagulation and renal concerns; crystalloids are first-line."},{"id":"vf04","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"List the body's normal mechanisms of heat production/conservation. Which of the following is NOT one of them?","options":["Shivering thermogenesis","Peripheral vasoconstriction","Behavioral changes (seeking warmth)","Active sweating across the body"],"answer":3,"explain":"Thermoregulation includes shivering thermogenesis, non-shivering (metabolic) thermogenesis, peripheral vasoconstriction to conserve heat, and behavioral responses. Dogs and cats do not rely on whole-body sweating; panting is for heat LOSS."},{"id":"adv01","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"The context-sensitive half-time of an opioid CRI refers to:","options":["The time to peak effect","The time for plasma concentration to fall 50% after stopping an infusion of a given duration","The elimination half-life at steady state","The onset time after a bolus"],"answer":1,"explain":"Context-sensitive half-time accounts for how infusion duration affects offset. Drugs like fentanyl accumulate with long CRIs, prolonging recovery; remifentanil's is nearly constant due to tissue esterase metabolism."},{"id":"adv02","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which drug is metabolized by plasma and tissue esterases, giving it an ultra-short, duration-independent recovery?","options":["Fentanyl","Morphine","Remifentanil","Methadone"],"answer":2,"explain":"Remifentanil is metabolized by nonspecific plasma/tissue esterases, independent of hepatic/renal function, giving a very short context-sensitive half-time ideal for titratable CRIs even in organ-compromised patients."},{"id":"adv03","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Maropitant provides which benefit relevant to anesthesia, beyond antiemesis?","options":["Profound sedation","Visceral analgesia (NK-1 antagonism) and possible MAC reduction","Prokinetic gastric emptying via 5-HT4 receptor agonism","Antihistamine (H1) antiemetic action"],"answer":1,"explain":"Maropitant is an NK-1 (substance P) antagonist; besides preventing vomiting, it provides visceral antinociception and may modestly reduce inhalant requirements during visceral surgery."},{"id":"adv04","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which neuromuscular blocking agent is non-depolarizing and reversed with neostigmine?","options":["Succinylcholine","Atracurium","Guaifenesin","Dantrolene"],"answer":1,"explain":"Atracurium is a non-depolarizing NMBA that competitively blocks the ACh receptor; it is reversed by acetylcholinesterase inhibitors like neostigmine (given with an anticholinergic). Succinylcholine is depolarizing and not reversed this way."},{"id":"adv05","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"When using a neuromuscular blocking agent, monitoring with a peripheral nerve stimulator is essential because:","options":["NMBAs provide profound analgesia that must be objectively measured","NMBAs cause paralysis without anesthesia or analgesia, masking light planes","NMBAs reduce inhalant requirement and can cause overdose","NMBAs can trigger malignant hyperthermia detectable by the stimulator"],"answer":1,"explain":"NMBAs paralyze but provide NO anesthesia or analgesia. A paralyzed patient cannot show movement signs of light anesthesia, so depth must be ensured by other means and blockade monitored via train-of-four."},{"id":"adv06","domain":"Monitoring","q":"The 'a-A gradient' or discrepancy between ETCO2 and PaCO2 widens with:","options":["Hypoventilation alone","Increased alveolar dead space (e.g., low cardiac output, PTE)","Increased cardiac output with improved pulmonary perfusion","Increased CO2 production from a hypermetabolic state"],"answer":1,"explain":"ETCO2 normally runs slightly below PaCO2. The gap widens with increased alveolar dead space — areas ventilated but not perfused — as in low cardiac output, hypotension, or pulmonary thromboembolism."},{"id":"adv07","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A pulse oximeter may give falsely normal readings in a patient with:","options":["Injected methylene blue dye","Carbon monoxide poisoning (carboxyhemoglobin)","Peripheral vasoconstriction from hypothermia","Dark nail-bed pigmentation at the probe site"],"answer":1,"explain":"Standard pulse oximeters cannot distinguish carboxyhemoglobin from oxyhemoglobin, giving falsely high SpO2 in CO poisoning. Co-oximetry is needed. Anemia and poor perfusion cause unreliable/low readings instead."},{"id":"adv08","domain":"Equipment","q":"An oxygen E-cylinder (green/white, in the US) is considered full at approximately:","options":["500 psi","1100 psi","2000-2200 psi","5000 psi"],"answer":2,"explain":"A full oxygen E-cylinder reads ~2000-2200 psi. Because oxygen is a compressed gas, the pressure falls linearly with use, so the gauge directly reflects remaining volume (unlike nitrous oxide, which is liquid/gas)."},{"id":"adv09","domain":"Equipment","q":"The pin index safety system on a gas cylinder exists to:","options":["Regulate flow rate","Prevent connecting a cylinder to the wrong gas yoke","Measure cylinder pressure","Scavenge waste gas"],"answer":1,"explain":"The Pin Index Safety System uses a unique pin arrangement for each gas so a cylinder can only attach to the correct yoke, preventing dangerous gas mix-ups (e.g., connecting N2O where O2 should be)."},{"id":"adv10","domain":"Physiology","q":"The Bohr effect describes how increased CO2 and decreased pH:","options":["Increase hemoglobin's affinity for carbon dioxide (the Haldane effect)","Decrease hemoglobin's affinity for oxygen, enhancing tissue offloading","Decrease red-cell 2,3-DPG, lowering oxygen release","Cause a leftward curve shift"],"answer":1,"explain":"The Bohr effect: in metabolically active (acidic, high-CO2) tissues, hemoglobin's O2 affinity decreases, promoting oxygen release where it's needed most — a rightward shift of the dissociation curve."},{"id":"adv11","domain":"Physiology","q":"Functional residual capacity (FRC) is reduced under anesthesia and in dorsal recumbency, predisposing to:","options":["Increased anatomic dead space","Atelectasis and hypoxemia","Increased lung compliance","Air trapping and hyperinflation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Reduced FRC (from recumbency, anesthesia, obesity, large abdomen) leads to small-airway closure and atelectasis, worsening V/Q matching and oxygenation. Recruitment maneuvers and preoxygenation help mitigate this."},{"id":"adv12","domain":"Physiology","q":"Preoxygenation before induction is beneficial because it:","options":["Speeds anesthetic uptake","Increases the oxygen reservoir in the lungs, delaying desaturation during apnea/intubation","Lowers MAC","Prevents laryngospasm"],"answer":1,"explain":"Preoxygenation (3-5 min of flow-by/mask O2) replaces nitrogen in the FRC with oxygen, building a reservoir that delays hypoxemia during the apnea of induction and intubation — critical in compromised or brachycephalic patients."},{"id":"adv13","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Ketamine at sub-anesthetic CRI doses provides analgesia primarily by:","options":["Mu-opioid agonism","NMDA receptor antagonism preventing central sensitization","COX inhibition","GABA potentiation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Low-dose ketamine antagonizes NMDA receptors, blunting wind-up/central sensitization and reducing opioid requirements. It is a valuable component of multimodal CRIs (e.g., MLK: morphine-lidocaine-ketamine)."},{"id":"adv14","domain":"Pain Management","q":"In an MLK (or FLK) CRI, the lidocaine component contributes which benefit (in dogs)?","options":["Deep sedation that lowers the opioid requirement","Analgesia, antiarrhythmic effect, and MAC reduction","NMDA-receptor antagonism that prevents wind-up","Reversal of opioid effects if oversedation develops"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lidocaine in a CRI (dogs) provides systemic analgesia, antiarrhythmic activity, prokinetic effects, and MAC reduction. It is used cautiously/avoided in cats due to a narrow toxic margin."},{"id":"adv15","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"The maximum recommended dose of lidocaine is lower in cats than dogs because cats:","options":["Metabolize local anesthetics faster, needing more frequent dosing","Are more sensitive to local anesthetic toxicity","Require higher doses per kilogram to achieve a block","Have a smaller circulating blood volume that concentrates the drug"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cats are markedly more sensitive to local anesthetic systemic toxicity, so maximum doses are substantially lower than in dogs. Always calculate total dose from ALL sources (blocks + CRI) to avoid toxicity."},{"id":"adv16","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"After return of spontaneous circulation (ROSC), an important post-cardiac-arrest care goal is to:","options":["Maintain 100% inspired oxygen indefinitely to maximize PaO2","Avoid hyperthermia and optimize oxygenation/perfusion","Hyperventilate aggressively to keep ETCO2 very low","Rapidly rewarm the patient into mild hyperthermia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Post-ROSC care focuses on optimizing ventilation/oxygenation (avoiding hyperoxia and hypercapnia), supporting blood pressure/perfusion, controlling seizures, and avoiding hyperthermia, which worsens neurologic injury."},{"id":"adv17","domain":"Complications","q":"A patient regurgitates under anesthesia. Beyond suctioning, an important step to prevent esophageal stricture is to:","options":["Deflate the endotracheal cuff to let fluid drain past the tube","Lavage the esophagus with water and suction, then consider neutralizing","Position the patient in dorsal recumbency to pool the fluid in the stomach","Withhold suctioning and allow the acid to be swallowed"],"answer":1,"explain":"Regurgitated acidic fluid can cause esophagitis and stricture. Keep the cuff inflated, suction the pharynx, lavage the esophagus with water (and suction), and lower the head to prevent aspiration."},{"id":"adv18","domain":"Complications","q":"Which finding most specifically suggests the anesthetic plane is too LIGHT?","options":["Absent palpebral reflex and a central eye position","Spontaneous movement, increased jaw tone, brisk palpebral reflex","A ventromedially rotated eye with loss of jaw tone","Widely dilated, unresponsive pupils"],"answer":1,"explain":"Signs of a light plane include purposeful movement, increased jaw/muscle tone, brisk palpebral reflex, tearing, nystagmus, increased HR/RR/BP in response to stimulation. Confirm before deepening, and rule out hypercapnia."},{"id":"adv19","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"An ASA Physical Status III patient is best described as one with:","options":["No systemic disease","Mild systemic disease","Severe systemic disease that limits activity but is not incapacitating","A moribund patient not expected to survive"],"answer":2,"explain":"ASA III = severe systemic disease limiting activity but not incapacitating (e.g., well-managed but significant cardiac disease). ASA I = healthy, II = mild disease, IV = severe life-threatening disease, V = moribund, E = emergency."},{"id":"adv20","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"The minimum monitoring during anesthesia per ACVAA guidelines should always assess:","options":["Blood pressure, urine output, and body temperature","Circulation, oxygenation, and ventilation","Anesthetic depth, muscle relaxation, and reflexes","Heart rate, respiratory rate, and capillary refill time"],"answer":1,"explain":"ACVAA monitoring guidelines emphasize continuous assessment of circulation (pulse, BP, ECG), oxygenation (SpO2, mucous membranes), and ventilation (RR, ETCO2), plus temperature — by a dedicated anesthetist."},{"id":"adv21","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"Why is a dedicated anesthetist (not also scrubbed into surgery) considered the standard of care?","options":["To keep an accurate anesthetic drug and controlled-substance log","To ensure continuous patient monitoring and rapid intervention","To manage the anesthetic machine and gas scavenging system","To reduce the amount of inhalant anesthetic used"],"answer":1,"explain":"A dedicated, attentive anesthetist watching the patient and monitors continuously is the single most important safety factor — enabling early detection and rapid correction of complications. This is core to AVTAA philosophy."},{"id":"adv22","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"The 'shock dose' of isotonic crystalloid is often cited as approximately one blood volume, which in the dog is about:","options":["10 mL/kg","20-30 mL/kg","80-90 mL/kg (given in fractions/boluses)","50-60 mL/kg"],"answer":2,"explain":"A dog's blood volume is ~80-90 mL/kg (cats ~50-60). The crystalloid shock dose approximates one blood volume but is given in titrated boluses (e.g., 1/4 dose) to effect, reassessing perfusion to avoid overload."},{"id":"np01","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which property of propofol contributes to its lack of accumulation and smooth recovery even after a CRI?","options":["Slow hepatic metabolism","Rapid redistribution and high clearance","Storage in fat with slow release","Renal-only elimination"],"answer":1,"explain":"Propofol has rapid redistribution from brain to peripheral tissues and high total body clearance (including extrahepatic metabolism), so plasma levels fall quickly when stopped, giving a smooth, quick recovery."},{"id":"np02","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Why does diazepam's propylene glycol carrier make it unsuitable for IM injection or rapid IV bolus?","options":["It causes marked histamine release and hypotension","It is painful, erratically absorbed IM, and can cause cardiovascular effects if given fast IV","It is neurotoxic and cannot contact nervous tissue","It is inactivated within seconds by light exposure"],"answer":1,"explain":"Diazepam is formulated in propylene glycol, which causes pain and unreliable absorption IM and can cause hypotension/arrhythmias if injected rapidly IV. Midazolam (water-soluble) is preferred for IM use."},{"id":"np03","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which opioid is most likely to cause histamine release if given rapidly IV?","options":["Fentanyl","Morphine","Methadone","Buprenorphine"],"answer":1,"explain":"Morphine can trigger histamine release with rapid IV administration, causing hypotension and urticaria. Give morphine slowly or IM/SC; fentanyl and methadone cause minimal histamine release."},{"id":"np04","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Tramadol's analgesic efficacy in dogs is considered limited primarily because:","options":["It is rapidly excreted unchanged","Dogs produce little of the active M1 metabolite","Dogs lack the mu-opioid receptors that tramadol targets","It is highly protein-bound, leaving little free drug"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tramadol's opioid effect depends on the M1 metabolite (O-desmethyltramadol). Dogs produce very little M1, so opioid-mediated analgesia is minimal; its monoamine reuptake effects provide some benefit but efficacy is inconsistent."},{"id":"np05","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which drug combination is commonly referred to as 'Telazol'?","options":["Tiletamine and zolazepam","Ketamine and midazolam","Xylazine and butorphanol","Acepromazine and morphine"],"answer":0,"explain":"Telazol is a 1:1 combination of tiletamine (a dissociative like ketamine) and zolazepam (a benzodiazepine). Recoveries can be rough and species-dependent in which component outlasts the other."},{"id":"np06","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A patient on chronic phenobarbital may require higher anesthetic drug doses because phenobarbital:","options":["Inhibits hepatic enzymes","Induces hepatic microsomal enzymes, increasing drug metabolism","Blocks drug absorption","Competes for plasma proteins only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Phenobarbital is a potent inducer of hepatic cytochrome P450 enzymes, accelerating metabolism of many co-administered drugs, so higher or more frequent doses may be needed (enzyme induction)."},{"id":"np07","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"The primary benefit of adding an opioid to a local anesthetic in an epidural is:","options":["Faster motor blockade","Prolonged and enhanced analgesia with less motor block","Reversal of the local anesthetic","Vasoconstriction at the site"],"answer":1,"explain":"Epidural opioids act on spinal opioid receptors to provide prolonged segmental analgesia while sparing motor function, complementing the local anesthetic's effect. Preservative-free formulations must be used."},{"id":"np08","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which alpha-2 agonist is most selective for the alpha-2 (vs alpha-1) receptor?","options":["Xylazine","Detomidine","Dexmedetomidine","Romifidine"],"answer":2,"explain":"Dexmedetomidine has the highest alpha-2:alpha-1 selectivity ratio (~1620:1), producing more predictable sedation/analgesia with fewer alpha-1 side effects than older agents like xylazine (~160:1)."},{"id":"np09","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Why is gabapentin used perioperatively, particularly for chronic or neuropathic pain?","options":["It is a potent NSAID","It modulates calcium channels to reduce neuropathic pain and anxiety","It is a GABA-B receptor agonist","It blocks NMDA receptors centrally"],"answer":1,"explain":"Gabapentin binds the alpha-2-delta subunit of voltage-gated calcium channels, reducing excitatory neurotransmitter release. It helps with neuropathic/chronic pain and provides mild anxiolysis/sedation perioperatively."},{"id":"np10","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which best describes the cardiovascular effect of a standard induction dose of fentanyl?","options":["Marked hypotension from vasodilation","Minimal direct cardiovascular depression, may cause bradycardia","Severe tachycardia","Strong positive inotropy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Fentanyl provides excellent cardiovascular stability with minimal myocardial depression, making it valuable for high-risk/cardiac patients. Vagally-mediated bradycardia is its main cardiovascular effect, treatable with anticholinergics."},{"id":"np11","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"What is the main reason ketamine should not be used as the sole anesthetic agent?","options":["It provides no somatic analgesia when used alone","It preserves muscle tone/reflexes and can cause rough recovery without a co-agent","It causes profound, unmanageable respiratory depression","It abolishes protective airway reflexes completely"],"answer":1,"explain":"Ketamine causes 'dissociative' anesthesia with retained muscle tone, cranial nerve reflexes, and potential for rough/excitatory recovery. It is combined with a benzodiazepine or alpha-2 agonist for muscle relaxation and smoother recovery."},{"id":"np12","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which inhalant has the lowest blood:gas partition coefficient, allowing the fastest changes in anesthetic depth?","options":["Isoflurane","Sevoflurane","Halothane","Desflurane"],"answer":3,"explain":"Desflurane has the lowest blood:gas solubility (~0.42), giving the most rapid induction, recovery, and depth changes. Its high vapor pressure requires a special heated vaporizer, and it is pungent (airway irritation)."},{"id":"np13","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which NSAID mechanism explains the GI and renal risks of non-selective NSAIDs?","options":["Inhibition of both COX-1 (protective) and COX-2 (inflammatory) enzymes","Selective COX-2 inhibition only","Inhibition of the lipoxygenase/leukotriene pathway","Blockade of prostaglandin receptors rather than their synthesis"],"answer":0,"explain":"Non-selective NSAIDs inhibit COX-1 (which maintains GI mucosa and renal blood flow) along with COX-2 (inflammation), explaining GI ulceration and renal risk. COX-2-preferential drugs aim to spare protective COX-1."},{"id":"np14","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Naloxone has a shorter duration than most opioids it reverses. The clinical implication is:","options":["Re-narcotization can occur, requiring re-dosing or a CRI","It permanently reverses the opioid","No monitoring is needed after reversal","It has no analgesic reversal"],"answer":0,"explain":"Because naloxone's half-life is shorter than drugs like morphine or hydromorphone, opioid effects (including respiratory depression) can return as naloxone wears off. Continued monitoring and repeat dosing or a CRI may be required."},{"id":"np15","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which agent provides reliable muscle relaxation and is often paired with ketamine to offset ketamine's muscle rigidity?","options":["Atropine","A benzodiazepine (e.g., midazolam or diazepam)","Glycopyrrolate","Hydromorphone"],"answer":1,"explain":"Benzodiazepines (midazolam, diazepam) provide central muscle relaxation that complements ketamine, smoothing induction and reducing rigidity and rough recoveries — the basis of 'ket-val'/'ket-mid' combinations."},{"id":"np16","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Acepromazine's antiarrhythmic and antiemetic-adjacent properties aside, its duration of action is best described as:","options":["Very short (under 30 min)","Long (several hours), and not reversible","Moderate (about 1 hour) and reversible with atipamezole","Long, but fully reversible with naloxone"],"answer":1,"explain":"Acepromazine has a long duration (often 4-8 hours) and no reversal agent. This must be considered in dosing — excessive doses cause prolonged sedation and hypotension with no way to antagonize the effect."},{"id":"np17","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"What is the rationale for using a 'balanced anesthesia' technique?","options":["To use the maximum dose of one drug","To combine lower doses of multiple agents, reducing the side effects of any single drug","To rely entirely on inhalant anesthesia for depth","To achieve anesthesia without providing any analgesia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Balanced anesthesia combines several agents (e.g., premed + induction + inhalant + analgesics) at lower individual doses, achieving the anesthetic goals while minimizing the dose-dependent adverse effects of each drug."},{"id":"np18","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which statement about nitrous oxide (N2O) is correct?","options":["It is a complete anesthetic on its own","It provides analgesia and MAC reduction but cannot be used alone due to its high MAC","It is metabolized to a toxic compound that must be reversed","It raises the blood:gas solubility of co-administered volatiles"],"answer":1,"explain":"N2O has a MAC over 100% in animals, so it cannot produce surgical anesthesia alone, but it provides analgesia and reduces the MAC of the primary inhalant. Diffusion hypoxia at discontinuation requires O2 supplementation."},{"id":"np19","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"The 'second gas effect' of nitrous oxide refers to:","options":["N2O slowing induction","High-volume uptake of N2O accelerating the alveolar rise of a co-administered volatile agent","N2O increasing the MAC of the co-administered volatile agent","N2O displacing the volatile agent from the alveoli"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rapid uptake of large volumes of N2O concentrates the remaining alveolar gases, speeding the rise in alveolar concentration of the second (volatile) agent and accelerating induction."},{"id":"np20","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which premedication choice is most appropriate for a healthy, anxious but otherwise stable dog?","options":["Acepromazine alone at a high dose","An opioid combined with a low dose of acepromazine or dexmedetomidine","Dexmedetomidine alone at a high dose","Ketamine alone IM"],"answer":1,"explain":"An opioid plus a sedative (acepromazine or low-dose dexmedetomidine) provides sedation, anxiolysis, and pre-emptive analgesia, smoothing induction and reducing induction/inhalant requirements in a stable patient."},{"id":"np21","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Lidocaine toxicity in dogs typically presents first as:","options":["Ventricular tachycardia as the earliest sign","Muscle tremors, nausea, and CNS signs progressing to seizures","Hypertension and reflex tachycardia","Hypersalivation and vomiting only, without CNS signs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Systemic lidocaine toxicity affects the CNS first — nausea, muscle tremors, and seizures — before cardiovascular depression. Respect cumulative dose limits across boluses, CRIs, and local blocks."},{"id":"np22","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Why is preservative-free morphine specifically required for epidural/intrathecal administration?","options":["Preservatives improve analgesia","Preservatives can be neurotoxic to spinal tissue","Preservatives shorten the duration of analgesia","Preservative-containing morphine is less potent"],"answer":1,"explain":"Preservatives (e.g., formaldehyde-releasing agents) in standard formulations can be neurotoxic when placed in the epidural/intrathecal space. Only preservative-free solutions should be used for neuraxial techniques."},{"id":"nphy01","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which formula correctly expresses oxygen delivery (DO2) to tissues?","options":["DO2 = cardiac output × arterial oxygen content","DO2 = cardiac output × PaO2","DO2 = hemoglobin concentration × oxygen saturation","DO2 = cardiac output × hemoglobin concentration"],"answer":0,"explain":"DO2 = cardiac output × arterial oxygen content (CaO2). CaO2 depends mainly on hemoglobin concentration and its saturation. Anemia, low CO, or desaturation all reduce oxygen delivery to tissues."},{"id":"nphy02","domain":"Physiology","q":"The majority of oxygen in arterial blood is transported:","options":["Dissolved in plasma","Bound to hemoglobin","As bicarbonate","Bound to albumin"],"answer":1,"explain":"Over 98% of oxygen is carried bound to hemoglobin; only a tiny fraction is dissolved in plasma (measured as PaO2). This is why hemoglobin concentration is critical to oxygen-carrying capacity."},{"id":"nphy03","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which best describes 'preload'?","options":["The resistance the heart pumps against","The volume/stretch of the ventricle at end-diastole","The heart rate","The contractile force"],"answer":1,"explain":"Preload is the end-diastolic ventricular volume/stretch (related to venous return). By the Frank-Starling mechanism, increased preload (to a point) increases stroke volume. Afterload is the resistance the ventricle ejects against."},{"id":"nphy04","domain":"Physiology","q":"During hypotension under anesthesia, which compensatory change would you expect if baroreceptor reflexes are intact?","options":["Increased heart rate with peripheral vasodilation","Increased heart rate and vasoconstriction","Vasoconstriction with reflex bradycardia","Increased contractility with decreased heart rate"],"answer":1,"explain":"Intact baroreflexes respond to low pressure with increased sympathetic outflow: tachycardia, increased contractility, and vasoconstriction. Anesthetics blunt this reflex, which is why anesthetized patients tolerate hypotension poorly."},{"id":"nphy05","domain":"Physiology","q":"What is the normal tidal volume range used to estimate ventilation in dogs and cats?","options":["5-7 mL/kg","10-15 mL/kg","20-30 mL/kg","1-2 mL/kg"],"answer":1,"explain":"Normal tidal volume is approximately 10-15 mL/kg. This guides manual and mechanical ventilation settings; excessive tidal volumes risk volutrauma, while inadequate volumes cause hypoventilation."},{"id":"nphy06","domain":"Physiology","q":"A capnograph shows ETCO2 rising from 40 to 60 mmHg over several minutes with a patent airway. What is the most appropriate intervention?","options":["Increase the vaporizer setting","Begin assisted or controlled ventilation to lower CO2","Decrease oxygen flow","Give a fluid bolus"],"answer":1,"explain":"A steadily rising ETCO2 with a patent airway indicates hypoventilation. The direct fix is to assist or control ventilation to normalize CO2, while also reassessing anesthetic depth — not increasing the inhalant."},{"id":"nphy07","domain":"Physiology","q":"What is the primary determinant of cerebral blood flow that is relevant during anesthesia of head-trauma patients?","options":["Arterial oxygen tension (PaO2)","Arterial CO2 (PaCO2)","Blood glucose concentration","Body temperature only"],"answer":1,"explain":"PaCO2 strongly regulates cerebral blood flow — hypercapnia causes cerebral vasodilation and raises intracranial pressure, while controlled mild hypocapnia can reduce it. Careful ventilation is critical in head-trauma anesthesia."},{"id":"nphy08","domain":"Physiology","q":"The dive in functional residual capacity (FRC) caused by general anesthesia predisposes the patient to:","options":["Increased anatomic dead space","Atelectasis and impaired oxygenation","Decreased airway resistance","Alveolar hyperinflation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Reduced FRC under anesthesia promotes small-airway closure and atelectasis, worsening ventilation-perfusion matching and oxygenation. Recumbency, obesity, and abdominal distension exacerbate it."},{"id":"nphy09","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which electrolyte abnormality most classically causes peaked T waves and bradycardia/arrhythmias under anesthesia?","options":["Hypokalemia","Hyperkalemia","Hypocalcemia","Hypernatremia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hyperkalemia (e.g., from urethral obstruction or uroabdomen) causes characteristic ECG changes — peaked T waves, widened QRS, bradycardia, and potentially fatal arrhythmias. It must be corrected before/around anesthesia."},{"id":"nphy10","domain":"Physiology","q":"Why does a urethral-obstructed cat require stabilization before anesthesia?","options":["To correct hypernatremia and metabolic alkalosis","To correct hyperkalemia and acidosis that endanger the heart","To treat hypocalcemia before induction","To lower an elevated blood glucose"],"answer":1,"explain":"Obstructed cats develop hyperkalemia and metabolic acidosis that cause life-threatening bradyarrhythmias. Stabilizing potassium (calcium gluconate, dextrose/insulin, fluids) and acid-base status before anesthesia is critical."},{"id":"nphy11","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which best describes the chemoreceptor that drives the secondary 'hypoxic drive' to breathe?","options":["Central chemoreceptors in the medulla","Peripheral chemoreceptors in the carotid and aortic bodies","Stretch receptors in the lung","Baroreceptors in the aorta"],"answer":1,"explain":"Peripheral chemoreceptors in the carotid and aortic bodies respond to low PaO2, providing the hypoxic drive. This becomes the main stimulus in chronic CO2 retainers, where high-flow oxygen must be used cautiously."},{"id":"nphy12","domain":"Physiology","q":"What happens to anesthetic requirements (MAC) during pregnancy?","options":["MAC increases significantly","MAC decreases (~25-40%)","MAC is unchanged","MAC decreases by roughly 5-10%"],"answer":1,"explain":"Pregnancy reduces MAC by roughly 25-40% due to hormonal (progesterone) effects, so less inhalant is needed. Combined with aortocaval compression and increased aspiration risk, pregnant patients require careful, reduced dosing."},{"id":"nphy13","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which change in the oxyhemoglobin dissociation curve INCREASES hemoglobin's affinity for oxygen (left shift)?","options":["Acidosis","Hypothermia and alkalosis","Increased 2,3-DPG","Hypercarbia"],"answer":1,"explain":"A left shift (higher O2 affinity, less tissue offloading) occurs with alkalosis, hypothermia, decreased 2,3-DPG, and hypocapnia. This is relevant in hypothermic anesthetized patients where oxygen unloading to tissues is impaired."},{"id":"nphy14","domain":"Physiology","q":"What is the primary physiologic consequence of aortocaval compression ('supine hypotensive syndrome') in a late-term pregnant patient in dorsal recumbency?","options":["Compression of the portal vein reducing hepatic blood flow","Compression of the caudal vena cava reducing venous return and cardiac output","Increased afterload from aortic compression raising cardiac output","Diaphragmatic compression reducing tidal volume"],"answer":1,"explain":"The gravid uterus compresses the caudal vena cava (and aorta) in dorsal recumbency, reducing venous return, cardiac output, and uteroplacental perfusion. Tilting the patient off midline relieves the compression."},{"id":"neq01","domain":"Equipment","q":"What is the purpose of the scavenging system on an anesthesia machine?","options":["To warm inspired gases","To collect and remove waste anesthetic gases to protect personnel","To measure ETCO2","To deliver oxygen"],"answer":1,"explain":"The scavenging system collects waste anesthetic gas from the pop-off valve and ventilator, removing it from the workspace to reduce chronic occupational exposure of staff to anesthetic gases."},{"id":"neq02","domain":"Equipment","q":"An endotracheal tube cuff is inflated primarily to:","options":["Hold the tube in position within the trachea","Create a seal preventing aspiration and gas leakage","Prevent tracheal collapse during ventilation","Reduce mechanical dead space within the airway"],"answer":1,"explain":"The cuff seals the trachea, preventing aspiration of fluids/material into the lungs and gas leakage around the tube. Overinflation risks tracheal mucosal injury or rupture; inflate to a minimal leak-free seal."},{"id":"neq03","domain":"Equipment","q":"Excessive endotracheal tube cuff pressure can cause:","options":["Improved sealing with no mucosal consequence","Tracheal mucosal ischemia, necrosis, or rupture","Reduced airway resistance and easier ventilation","Loss of the seal due to over-distension of the cuff"],"answer":1,"explain":"Overinflated cuffs exert pressure on the tracheal mucosa, causing ischemia, necrosis, or even tracheal tears (especially in cats). Use minimal occlusive volume and never overinflate; check before repositioning."},{"id":"neq04","domain":"Equipment","q":"A nitrous oxide cylinder gauge reads a steady pressure even as gas is used because:","options":["A pressure-reducing regulator holds the outlet pressure constant","N2O exists as a liquid; pressure stays constant until liquid is gone","N2O is far more compressible than oxygen, so pressure falls slowly","The cylinder continuously refills from a reserve manifold"],"answer":1,"explain":"N2O is stored as a liquid in equilibrium with its vapor; the gauge reflects vapor pressure, which stays constant until nearly all liquid is consumed, then drops rapidly. Cylinder weight, not pressure, indicates remaining N2O."},{"id":"neq05","domain":"Equipment","q":"What does a sudden inability to keep the reservoir bag inflated during a leak test most likely indicate?","options":["Excessive fresh gas flow overinflating the bag","A leak in the breathing circuit","A properly seated CO2 absorbent canister","An oversized reservoir bag for the patient"],"answer":1,"explain":"If the bag won't hold pressure with the pop-off closed, there is a leak — check connections, the ET tube cuff, the reservoir bag, soda lime canister seals, and the circuit hoses before use."},{"id":"neq06","domain":"Equipment","q":"In a circle (rebreathing) system, unidirectional valves serve to:","options":["Vent excess circuit pressure to the scavenger","Direct gas flow in one direction so the patient inhales fresh gas and exhales toward the absorber","Regulate the rate of fresh gas entering the circuit","Convert liquid anesthetic to vapor"],"answer":1,"explain":"The inspiratory and expiratory one-way valves ensure gas moves in a single direction around the circle — inhaled gas comes from the fresh/absorbed side and exhaled gas passes through the CO2 absorber, preventing rebreathing of CO2."},{"id":"neq07","domain":"Equipment","q":"Why should you select an endotracheal tube and also have one size smaller and larger ready?","options":["Because a fresh sterile tube is needed for each intubation attempt","Because airway size varies and a different size may be needed for a proper, atraumatic fit","So the largest possible tube can always be placed to lower resistance","Because tube size is chosen by patient age rather than airway anatomy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Estimating tube size is approximate; airway anatomy varies (especially in brachycephalics or with laryngeal edema). Having a size up and down ready allows a proper, atraumatic seal without delay."},{"id":"neq08","domain":"Equipment","q":"A flowmeter measures:","options":["The anesthetic agent concentration delivered","The rate of fresh gas (oxygen) flow in L/min","The pressure remaining in the oxygen cylinder","The pressure within the breathing circuit"],"answer":1,"explain":"The flowmeter controls and displays fresh gas flow (typically oxygen) in liters per minute. Adequate flow is essential for non-rebreathing systems and for denitrogenation/preoxygenation."},{"id":"neq09","domain":"Equipment","q":"What is the consequence of exhausted CO2 absorbent (soda lime) that is not replaced?","options":["A steady drop in the inspired oxygen concentration","Rebreathing of CO2 leading to hypercapnia","Progressive lightening of the anesthetic plane","Overheating and melting of the absorbent canister"],"answer":1,"explain":"Spent soda lime no longer absorbs CO2, so the patient rebreathes exhaled CO2, causing hypercapnia and respiratory acidosis. Color change, hardness, and lack of heat indicate exhaustion — replace promptly."},{"id":"neq10","domain":"Equipment","q":"Which describes the correct placement check for an endotracheal tube?","options":["Visualize the tube passing between the arytenoids, confirm with capnography and chest movement","Confirm placement solely by palpating a single firm tube in the neck","Rely on the reservoir bag moving with each breath alone","Judge placement by return of the swallowing reflex"],"answer":0,"explain":"Confirm correct (tracheal, not esophageal) placement by direct visualization of the tube passing through the larynx, a normal capnograph waveform, bilateral chest movement, and breath sounds. Capnography is the most reliable confirmation."},{"id":"neq11","domain":"Equipment","q":"A pressure-relief (pop-off/APL) valve in a rebreathing circuit should normally be:","options":["Kept fully closed to maintain circuit pressure","Open during spontaneous ventilation, briefly closed only for manual breaths","Closed during recovery until the patient is extubated","Kept half-closed throughout to conserve anesthetic gas"],"answer":1,"explain":"The pop-off valve stays open during spontaneous breathing to vent excess gas and prevent pressure buildup. It is closed only momentarily to deliver a manual breath, then immediately reopened to prevent barotrauma."},{"id":"neq12","domain":"Equipment","q":"What is the function of a pressure manometer on the anesthesia machine?","options":["To measure anesthetic concentration","To display airway/circuit pressure, helping prevent barotrauma","To scavenge gas","To control oxygen flow"],"answer":1,"explain":"The manometer shows breathing-circuit pressure. Monitoring it during manual or mechanical ventilation helps avoid excessive airway pressure (barotrauma) and confirms a sealed circuit during leak checks."},{"id":"nmon01","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A capnograph showing a gradually rising baseline (the inspired CO2 not returning to zero) suggests:","options":["Hyperventilation","Rebreathing of CO2, often from exhausted absorbent or a faulty valve","Esophageal intubation","Apnea"],"answer":1,"explain":"An elevated inspired (baseline) CO2 on the capnograph means the patient is rebreathing CO2 — commonly from exhausted soda lime, a stuck one-way valve, or inadequate fresh gas flow in a non-rebreathing system."},{"id":"nmon02","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Why can a patient on 100% oxygen maintain a normal SpO2 while still being dangerously hypercapnic?","options":["The pulse oximeter automatically corrects for rising CO2 levels","Oxygenation can be preserved by high FiO2 even when ventilation (CO2 removal) is inadequate","High oxygen flow flushes CO2 out of the lungs, masking hypercapnia","Hypercapnia causes vasodilation that improves SpO2 accuracy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Oxygenation and ventilation are distinct. A high inspired oxygen fraction keeps SpO2 normal even during hypoventilation, while CO2 still accumulates — which is why capnography is essential alongside pulse oximetry."},{"id":"nmon03","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A patient on 100% oxygen can maintain a normal SpO2 despite significant hypoventilation because:","options":["Oxygenation and ventilation are independent; high FiO2 maintains saturation while CO2 still rises","The large oxygen reserve flushes accumulated CO2 from the alveoli","Rising CO2 shifts the curve, artificially raising the SpO2 reading","Peripheral vasoconstriction concentrates oxygenated hemoglobin at the probe"],"answer":0,"explain":"With a high inspired oxygen fraction, arterial oxygen saturation can stay normal even during hypoventilation because there is a large oxygen reserve — but CO2 still accumulates. This is why capnography is essential alongside pulse oximetry."},{"id":"nmon04","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Where are common sites to place a pulse oximeter probe in an anesthetized patient?","options":["Only on thick, heavily pigmented footpads","Tongue, lip, toe web, prepuce/vulva, or ear","The haired skin over the dorsum or flank","Directly over a large muscle belly such as the quadriceps"],"answer":1,"explain":"Transmittance probes work on non-pigmented, thin, perfused tissue: the tongue is most common, plus lip, ear, toe web, prepuce, or vulva. Reflectance probes can be placed rectally. Poor perfusion or pigment reduces accuracy."},{"id":"nmon05","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A widening gap between palpated/Doppler pulse strength and a falling oscillometric blood pressure should prompt the technician to:","options":["Increase the vaporizer setting to stabilize the reading","Assess the patient for developing hypotension and notify the veterinarian","Switch to a larger cuff and continue without further action","Document the value and recheck only at the end of surgery"],"answer":1,"explain":"Discrepancies and trends matter more than single values. A weakening pulse and falling BP indicate developing hypotension — assess depth, fluids, and perfusion, and alert the veterinarian to intervene early."},{"id":"nmon06","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Which is the most reliable indicator of adequate tissue perfusion during anesthesia?","options":["A single systolic blood pressure reading","Trends in blood pressure, capillary refill time, pulse quality, and mucous membrane color together","Pulse oximetry (SpO2) reading alone","End-tidal CO2 value alone"],"answer":1,"explain":"No single parameter tells the whole story; perfusion is assessed by integrating blood pressure trends, CRT, pulse quality, mucous membrane color, ETCO2, and temperature. Trends over time are more informative than isolated values."},{"id":"nmon07","domain":"Monitoring","q":"An ECG shows a prolonged pause with no P wave or QRS, followed by resumption. This is most consistent with:","options":["Ventricular tachycardia","Sinus arrest/block","Atrial fibrillation","Normal sinus rhythm"],"answer":1,"explain":"A pause with absent P-QRS-T complexes suggests sinus arrest or block (often vagally mediated, e.g., from ocular pressure, visceral traction, or opioids/alpha-2 agonists). Address the cause; anticholinergics may be indicated."},{"id":"nmon08","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Direct (invasive) arterial blood pressure monitoring is considered the gold standard because it:","options":["It is faster and easier to set up than an oscillometric cuff","Provides continuous, beat-to-beat accurate pressure and allows arterial blood sampling","It also directly measures cardiac output and central venous pressure","It requires no transducer, tubing, or calibration"],"answer":1,"explain":"An arterial catheter transduced to a monitor gives continuous, real-time, accurate blood pressure and allows arterial blood gas sampling. It is invaluable in critical/unstable patients but requires technical skill to place and maintain."},{"id":"nmon09","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Hypothermia under anesthesia can cause which monitoring change?","options":["Increased anesthetic requirement (higher MAC)","Bradycardia, decreased MAC, prolonged recovery, and unreliable pulse oximetry","Tachycardia with increased cardiac output","Peripheral vasodilation with warm, well-perfused extremities"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hypothermia lowers MAC, slows heart rate and metabolism, prolongs drug effects/recovery, impairs coagulation, and can make pulse oximetry unreliable due to peripheral vasoconstriction. Active warming and temperature monitoring are essential."},{"id":"nmon10","domain":"Monitoring","q":"What does capnography reveal almost immediately during cardiac arrest?","options":["A gradual rise in ETCO2 from CO2 accumulation","A sudden drop in ETCO2 toward zero due to loss of pulmonary blood flow","A rising inspired CO2 baseline","An unchanged waveform with a normal plateau"],"answer":1,"explain":"During cardiac arrest, pulmonary blood flow ceases, so CO2 stops being delivered to the lungs and ETCO2 falls sharply. A rising ETCO2 during CPR is an encouraging sign of effective compressions or ROSC."},{"id":"nmon11","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Which is a limitation of oscillometric (automated cuff) blood pressure monitoring?","options":["It gives continuous beat-to-beat readings like an arterial line","It is less reliable in very small patients, with arrhythmias, or at low pressures","It requires arterial catheterization to obtain a reading","It becomes more accurate as blood pressure falls"],"answer":1,"explain":"Oscillometric devices can be inaccurate in very small patients, during motion or arrhythmias, and at low blood pressures. Proper cuff size (~40% of limb circumference) and trending improve reliability."},{"id":"nmon12","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A blood pressure cuff that is too narrow for the limb will give readings that are:","options":["Falsely low, as with a cuff that is too wide","Falsely high","Accurate, since cuff width does not affect readings","Erratic and non-reproducible from beat to beat"],"answer":1,"explain":"A too-narrow (or too-tight) cuff requires more pressure to occlude the artery, falsely elevating the reading. A too-wide cuff falsely lowers it. Cuff width should be ~40% of limb circumference."},{"id":"npn01","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Physiologic signs that may indicate inadequate analgesia (nociception) under anesthesia include:","options":["Bradycardia and hypotension during surgical manipulation","Increasing heart rate, blood pressure, and respiratory rate in response to surgical stimulation","A rising end-tidal CO2 with otherwise stable vital signs","Return of the palpebral reflex without any cardiovascular change"],"answer":1,"explain":"Nociception triggers a sympathetic response — rising heart rate, blood pressure, and respiratory rate during noxious stimulation. This signals the need for additional analgesia rather than simply deepening the inhalant."},{"id":"npn02","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Why is treating only with increased inhalant (rather than analgesics) a poor strategy for intraoperative nociception?","options":["Inhalants are potent analgesics, so higher doses fully control pain","Inhalants provide minimal analgesia and cause dose-dependent cardiovascular depression","Higher inhalant concentrations raise blood pressure and worsen bleeding","Deep inhalant planes provide pre-emptive analgesia against wind-up"],"answer":1,"explain":"Volatile inhalants provide little true analgesia; deepening them to control nociceptive responses causes dose-dependent hypotension and respiratory depression. Adding analgesics (opioid, local block, CRI) is safer and more effective."},{"id":"npn03","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Which statement about pre-emptive analgesia is correct?","options":["Reserving analgesics until the patient shows signs of pain postoperatively","Administering analgesia before tissue injury reduces central sensitization and total analgesic needs","Using only long-acting local anesthetics for the entire procedure","Layering inhalant depth during surgery to prevent patient movement"],"answer":1,"explain":"Pre-emptive analgesia (before the noxious stimulus) blunts the establishment of central sensitization/wind-up, lowering pain intensity and overall analgesic requirements postoperatively."},{"id":"npn04","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A constant rate infusion (CRI) is preferred over intermittent boluses for some analgesics because it:","options":["Produces higher peak concentrations for a faster onset","Maintains stable plasma concentrations, avoiding peaks and troughs","Allows a much larger total drug dose to be given safely","Removes the need to give a loading dose first"],"answer":1,"explain":"A CRI maintains a steady plasma drug level, providing consistent analgesia and avoiding the breakthrough pain (troughs) and side effects (peaks) of intermittent bolus dosing. A loading dose is usually given first."},{"id":"npn05","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Behavioral signs of pain in cats can be subtle but include:","options":["Increased playfulness and a heightened appetite","Hiding, decreased grooming, hunched posture, and reduced appetite","Loud, continuous purring that reliably signals contentment","Seeking out human interaction more than usual"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cats often mask pain. Signs include hiding, reduced grooming, a hunched/tucked posture, decreased appetite, reluctance to move, and altered facial expression (Feline Grimace Scale). Recognizing these prompts appropriate analgesia."},{"id":"npn06","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Which multimodal combination targets the most points in the pain pathway?","options":["An opioid combined with a benzodiazepine and inhalant","An opioid + NSAID + local/regional block ± alpha-2 or ketamine","Two different opioids given together","A high-dose opioid plus an increased inhalant concentration"],"answer":1,"explain":"Combining an opioid (central), NSAID (peripheral inflammation), a local/regional block (transduction/transmission), and an NMDA antagonist or alpha-2 (modulation) targets multiple sites, maximizing analgesia while minimizing each drug's dose."},{"id":"npn07","domain":"Pain Management","q":"The Feline Grimace Scale assesses pain in cats based on:","options":["Vocalization frequency and pitch","Facial action units such as ear position, orbital tightening, and muzzle tension","Response to gentle palpation of the surgical site","Posture, gait, and overall activity level"],"answer":1,"explain":"The validated Feline Grimace Scale scores facial features — ear position, orbital tightening, muzzle tension, whisker position, and head position — providing an objective, repeatable pain assessment in cats."},{"id":"npn08","domain":"Pain Management","q":"When is it appropriate to administer an NSAID perioperatively?","options":["To any patient as long as an opioid is given alongside it","Only to normovolemic, normotensive patients with adequate renal function and no contraindications","To hypovolemic patients once anesthesia has stabilized them","To patients already receiving corticosteroids for added anti-inflammatory effect"],"answer":1,"explain":"NSAIDs are safe when the patient is well-perfused with normal renal function and no GI/coagulation/steroid contraindications. They are avoided in hypovolemic, hypotensive, or renally compromised patients due to prostaglandin-dependent renal blood flow."},{"id":"nloc01","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Which nerve block desensitizes the mandibular (lower) teeth?","options":["Infraorbital block","Inferior alveolar (mandibular) block","Maxillary block","Auriculotemporal block"],"answer":1,"explain":"The inferior alveolar (mandibular) block desensitizes the lower dental arcade by anesthetizing the inferior alveolar nerve as it enters the mandibular foramen on the lingual aspect of the mandible."},{"id":"nloc02","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Adding epinephrine to a local anesthetic solution primarily serves to:","options":["Buffer the solution to reduce stinging on injection","Cause local vasoconstriction, prolonging duration and reducing systemic absorption","Speed the onset of the block by raising tissue pH","Add analgesia through direct beta-2 receptor activation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Epinephrine causes local vasoconstriction that slows systemic absorption, prolonging the block's duration and reducing peak plasma levels (lower toxicity). Avoid in areas with end-arterial supply (e.g., extremities/digits)."},{"id":"nloc03","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Why must you aspirate before injecting a local anesthetic for a nerve block?","options":["To confirm the needle tip sits within the nerve sheath","To check for inadvertent intravascular placement and avoid IV injection","To draw back air bubbles that could cause an embolism","To lower injection pressure and prevent perineural swelling"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aspirating before injection checks that the needle is not in a blood vessel. Inadvertent IV injection of local anesthetic (especially bupivacaine) can cause severe systemic toxicity, including seizures and cardiac arrest."},{"id":"nloc04","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"A brachycephalic dog needs a forelimb procedure. Which regional technique is appropriate?","options":["Epidural","Brachial plexus block or RUMM (radial-ulnar-median-musculocutaneous) block","Femoral nerve block","Infraorbital block"],"answer":1,"explain":"The thoracic limb is anesthetized with a brachial plexus block or a RUMM block (distal forelimb). Femoral/sciatic blocks and epidurals target the pelvic limbs; dental blocks target the head."},{"id":"nloc05","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"The maximum total dose of bupivacaine is lower than lidocaine mainly because bupivacaine is:","options":["More water-soluble, so it distributes and clears quickly","More potent and more cardiotoxic","Less protein-bound","Metabolized faster"],"answer":1,"explain":"Bupivacaine is more potent and notably more cardiotoxic than lidocaine, with a narrower safety margin, so maximum cumulative doses are lower. Always total all sources (blocks, line blocks, splash) to stay under the limit."},{"id":"nloc06","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"The treatment for severe bupivacaine-induced cardiotoxicity (refractory to standard resuscitation) is:","options":["Flumazenil to reverse the central nervous system effects","Intravenous lipid emulsion (ILE) therapy","Naloxone","Atropine alone"],"answer":1,"explain":"Intravenous lipid emulsion ('lipid rescue') is the specific therapy for severe local anesthetic systemic toxicity, particularly bupivacaine — it acts as a lipid sink and improves cardiac function alongside standard CPR."},{"id":"nloc07","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"An intratesticular block during castration provides analgesia by:","options":["Blocking the pudendal nerve as it exits the pelvis","Anesthetizing the spermatic cord/testicular nerves locally, reducing nociception and anesthetic needs","Numbing only the scrotal skin at the incision site","Providing systemic analgesia after absorption into the circulation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Injecting local anesthetic into the testis diffuses along the spermatic cord, blocking the spermatic plexus and reducing intraoperative nociception and inhalant requirements — a simple, effective multimodal addition for castration."},{"id":"ner01","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"In the RECOVER BLS sequence, what is prioritized immediately upon recognizing cardiopulmonary arrest?","options":["Drawing up emergency drugs before starting compressions","Starting chest compressions and securing the airway/ventilation without delay","Establishing intravenous access before beginning compressions","Confirming arrest with an ECG before starting compressions"],"answer":1,"explain":"Basic Life Support — high-quality chest compressions and ventilation — is started immediately on recognizing arrest. Early, minimally-interrupted compressions are the highest priority; drugs and advanced steps follow."},{"id":"ner02","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"For a medium-to-large dog, the recommended hand position for external chest compressions is:","options":["Over the sternum at the costochondral junction near the widest part of the chest","Directly over the heart at the point of maximal impulse, as in cats and small dogs","Over the caudal sternum near the xiphoid process","Cranial to the forelimb over the manubrium"],"answer":0,"explain":"In most dogs, compressions are delivered over the widest portion of the lateral chest (lateral recumbency). Keeled-chest dogs may use a sternal/dorsal approach. Compress 1/3-1/2 chest width with full recoil."},{"id":"ner03","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Why are chest compressions rotated to a new compressor every 2 minutes during CPR?","options":["To allow the heart to refill fully between compression cycles","Because compressor fatigue reduces compression quality over time","To alternate between thoracic-pump and cardiac-pump techniques","To lower the risk of rib fractures by sharing the workload"],"answer":1,"explain":"Compression quality declines with fatigue within about 2 minutes. Rotating compressors every cycle (coinciding with rhythm checks) maintains effective depth and rate, sustaining coronary and cerebral perfusion."},{"id":"ner04","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Which rhythm is potentially shockable (defibrillation indicated) during CPR?","options":["Asystole","Pulseless electrical activity","Ventricular fibrillation/pulseless ventricular tachycardia","Sinus bradycardia"],"answer":2,"explain":"Ventricular fibrillation and pulseless ventricular tachycardia are shockable rhythms treated with electrical defibrillation. Asystole and PEA are non-shockable and managed with CPR plus epinephrine ± atropine."},{"id":"ner05","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Atropine is most useful during CPR when the arrest is:","options":["In arrest due to ventricular fibrillation","Vagally mediated or associated with bradycardia/asystole","In arrest caused by severe hyperkalemia","In pulseless ventricular tachycardia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Atropine counters high vagal tone and is indicated in bradyarrhythmic or vagally-mediated arrest (e.g., from visceral/ocular stimulation). It is given with epinephrine in asystole/PEA per RECOVER guidelines."},{"id":"ner06","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"What is the purpose of capnography during CPR beyond confirming intubation?","options":["Directly measuring arterial oxygen saturation","Gauging compression effectiveness and detecting return of spontaneous circulation (ROSC)","Precisely quantifying cardiac output in mL/min","Confirming the depth of anesthesia"],"answer":1,"explain":"ETCO2 during CPR reflects pulmonary blood flow generated by compressions. Higher values suggest effective compressions; an abrupt rise often signals ROSC. Persistently very low ETCO2 indicates poor perfusion."},{"id":"ner07","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Naloxone may be used during resuscitation of an arrested patient if:","options":["The patient received only alpha-2 agonists like dexmedetomidine","Opioids contributed to respiratory depression/arrest","Local anesthetic (bupivacaine) toxicity is suspected","Benzodiazepine oversedation is suspected"],"answer":1,"explain":"If opioids contributed to respiratory depression and arrest, naloxone reversal can help. Reversal agents (naloxone, atipamezole, flumazenil) are considered when the corresponding drug may have caused the deterioration."},{"id":"ner08","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"During anesthetic emergencies, the single most important early action when a problem is detected is to:","options":["Increase the inhalant to ensure the patient does not become aware","Reduce/turn off the anesthetic agent and ensure oxygenation while calling for help","Give an intravenous fluid bolus before adjusting anesthetic depth","Administer epinephrine immediately"],"answer":1,"explain":"When a patient deteriorates, lightening the anesthetic (turning down/off the vaporizer) reduces cardiovascular and respiratory depression, while ensuring 100% oxygen and ventilation and summoning help — then treat the specific cause."},{"id":"ner09","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"What defines 'return of spontaneous circulation' (ROSC)?","options":["A single palpable pulse felt during a pause in compressions","A sustained, palpable pulse and effective cardiac rhythm return","Organized electrical activity on the ECG, regardless of pulse","A rising ETCO2 measured during ongoing chest compressions"],"answer":1,"explain":"ROSC is the return of a sustained spontaneous pulse and perfusing cardiac rhythm. It marks the transition to post-cardiac-arrest care: optimizing oxygenation, blood pressure, glucose, and temperature while monitoring for re-arrest."},{"id":"ncalc01","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 4 kg cat needs ketamine at 5 mg/kg. Concentration is 100 mg/mL. What volume is drawn up?","options":["0.1 mL","0.2 mL","0.4 mL","2.0 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dose = 4 kg × 5 mg/kg = 20 mg. Volume = 20 mg ÷ 100 mg/mL = 0.2 mL. Small-volume doses in cats demand careful measurement with appropriately sized syringes."},{"id":"ncalc02","domain":"Calculations","q":"A dog weighs 30 kg and needs a surgical crystalloid rate of 5 mL/kg/hr. What is the hourly rate?","options":["60 mL/hr","150 mL/hr","300 mL/hr","450 mL/hr"],"answer":1,"explain":"30 kg × 5 mL/kg/hr = 150 mL/hr. Set the fluid pump accordingly and adjust for blood pressure, blood loss, and patient response, avoiding volume overload."},{"id":"ncalc03","domain":"Calculations","q":"Convert 0.5 mg to micrograms.","options":["5 mcg","50 mcg","500 mcg","5000 mcg"],"answer":2,"explain":"1 mg = 1000 mcg, so 0.5 mg = 500 mcg. Unit conversions are a frequent source of dosing errors — always confirm mg vs mcg, especially with potent drugs like fentanyl (dosed in mcg)."},{"id":"ncalc04","domain":"Calculations","q":"A fentanyl CRI is set at 5 mcg/kg/hr for a 20 kg dog. Fentanyl is 50 mcg/mL. What pump rate in mL/hr is needed?","options":["1 mL/hr","2 mL/hr","4 mL/hr","10 mL/hr"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dose = 5 mcg/kg/hr × 20 kg = 100 mcg/hr. Volume = 100 mcg/hr ÷ 50 mcg/mL = 2 mL/hr. Always confirm the drug concentration before programming the pump."},{"id":"ncalc05","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 10 kg patient receives a 90 mL/kg shock dose of crystalloid given in 1/4 increments. What is one increment volume?","options":["90 mL","225 mL","450 mL","900 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Full shock dose = 10 kg × 90 mL/kg = 900 mL. One-quarter increment = 900 ÷ 4 = 225 mL, given over ~15 minutes with reassessment of perfusion between boluses to avoid overload."},{"id":"ncalc06","domain":"Calculations","q":"A drug is dosed at 0.2 mg/kg for a 25 kg dog. The concentration is 1 mg/mL. What volume is needed?","options":["50 mL","5 mL","10 mL","0.5 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dose = 25 kg × 0.2 mg/kg = 5 mg. Volume = 5 mg ÷ 1 mg/mL = 5 mL. Double-check the math and the label concentration before drawing up."},{"id":"ncalc07","domain":"Calculations","q":"To make a 2 mcg/mL fentanyl CRI bag, you add 250 mcg of fentanyl to a fluid bag. What bag volume gives that concentration?","options":["62.5 mL","125 mL","250 mL","500 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Concentration = total drug ÷ volume. 250 mcg ÷ 2 mcg/mL = 125 mL. Verifying the final concentration after compounding a CRI prevents accidental over- or under-dosing."},{"id":"ncalc08","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 50 kg dog needs a lidocaine CRI at 50 mcg/kg/min. How many mcg/min are delivered?","options":["250 mcg/min","25000 mcg/min","2500 mcg/min","5000 mcg/min"],"answer":2,"explain":"50 mcg/kg/min × 50 kg = 2500 mcg/min (2.5 mg/min). Note lidocaine CRIs are often dosed per minute, unlike fentanyl per hour — read units carefully when setting the pump."},{"id":"nsp01","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Rabbits are challenging to intubate primarily because of:","options":["An elongated soft palate covering the glottis, as seen in brachycephalic breeds","A small mouth, large tongue, and deep narrow oropharynx limiting visualization","Complete cartilaginous tracheal rings prone to collapse","A laterally displaced larynx requiring a lateral approach"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rabbits have a narrow, deep oral cavity, a large tongue, and a caudally positioned glottis, making direct visualization difficult. Blind or endoscope-guided intubation, or supraglottic devices, are often used; they are also prone to laryngospasm."},{"id":"nsp02","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Why are rabbits and many small mammals NOT routinely fasted for long periods before anesthesia?","options":["They cannot vomit, and prolonged fasting risks GI stasis and hypoglycemia","Fasting rapidly triggers dangerous hyperkalemia","An empty stomach greatly increases their risk of gastric dilatation-volvulus","Their unique calcium metabolism causes hypercalcemia when food is withheld"],"answer":0,"explain":"Rabbits and rodents cannot vomit, so aspiration risk from food is low, while prolonged fasting causes dangerous GI stasis and hypoglycemia. Only brief fasting (to clear the mouth) is used in these species."},{"id":"nsp03","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A key anesthetic concern in sighthounds (e.g., Greyhounds) is:","options":["High body fat that prolongs the action of lipophilic anesthetics","Prolonged recovery from thiobarbiturates and altered drug metabolism/low body fat","A genetic MDR1 mutation causing severe ivermectin and opioid sensitivity","Malignant hyperthermia triggered by all inhalant anesthetics"],"answer":1,"explain":"Sighthounds have low body fat and altered hepatic metabolism, leading to prolonged recoveries from older redistribution-dependent drugs (thiobarbiturates) and sensitivity to some agents. Propofol/alfaxalone and careful titration are preferred."},{"id":"nsp04","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Equine anesthesia carries a notably higher mortality risk than small animal anesthesia largely because of:","options":["A high risk of vomiting and aspiration during induction and recovery","Recovery complications, myopathy/neuropathy from positioning, and cardiovascular demands","Extreme sensitivity to inhalants causing rapid, unpredictable overdose","Their inability to be intubated, requiring mask delivery of anesthesia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Horses face higher anesthetic mortality due to their size — risks include recovery injuries (fractures during standing), positioning-related myopathy/neuropathy, and significant cardiovascular and ventilatory challenges under general anesthesia."},{"id":"nsp05","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Birds have a unique respiratory system featuring:","options":["A muscular diaphragm and highly compliant alveoli, as in mammals","Air sacs and a flow-through (unidirectional) lung system","Large bellows-like lungs that expand and contract with tidal breaths","Bidirectional airflow through blind-ended alveolar sacs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Birds have air sacs and parabronchi providing unidirectional, highly efficient gas exchange and no functional diaphragm. They depend on body-wall movement to ventilate; restraint that limits keel movement can rapidly cause hypoventilation."},{"id":"nsp06","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A major anesthetic risk in obese patients is:","options":["Rapid, unpredictable drug redistribution causing anesthetic underdosing","Reduced functional residual capacity, hypoventilation, and difficulty dosing on body weight","Increased chest-wall compliance leading to excessive tidal volumes","A high risk of hypoglycemia from depleted glycogen stores"],"answer":1,"explain":"Obesity reduces FRC and chest-wall compliance (hypoventilation, atelectasis), complicates venous access and dosing (dose to lean body weight for many drugs), and increases aspiration and positioning risks."},{"id":"nsp07","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Pediatric patients are prone to hypothermia under anesthesia because of:","options":["A very low metabolic rate that produces little metabolic heat","A high surface-area-to-body-mass ratio and immature thermoregulation","Excessive peripheral vasodilation caused by high body-fat insulation","Continuous evaporative heat loss from panting"],"answer":1,"explain":"Neonates/pediatrics have a high surface-area-to-mass ratio, little insulating fat, and immature thermoregulation, losing heat rapidly. Active warming, warm fluids, and minimizing exposure are essential, along with glucose monitoring."},{"id":"ncx01","domain":"Complications","q":"A patient under anesthesia develops a rising ETCO2, increasing temperature, and tachycardia. The first concern should be:","options":["Hypothermia causing shivering","A hypermetabolic state such as malignant hyperthermia or inadequate ventilation","A light plane of anesthesia alone","An acute anaphylactic drug reaction"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rising ETCO2 with hyperthermia and tachycardia raises concern for a hypermetabolic crisis (e.g., malignant hyperthermia) or severe hypoventilation/rebreathing. Verify ventilation/absorbent, discontinue triggering agents, cool the patient, and treat aggressively."},{"id":"ncx02","domain":"Complications","q":"The most appropriate first response to anesthetic-related hypotension (after confirming depth) is usually to:","options":["Give atropine to raise the blood pressure","Decrease anesthetic depth and give a fluid bolus, then consider inotropes/vasopressors","Start a phenylephrine infusion before adjusting anesthetic depth","Administer furosemide to improve renal perfusion"],"answer":1,"explain":"For anesthetic hypotension, first reduce inhalant depth (the common cause), then administer a crystalloid bolus; if pressure remains low, add an inotrope (dobutamine) or vasopressor based on the underlying problem."},{"id":"ncx03","domain":"Complications","q":"Bradycardia under a dexmedetomidine infusion with a high blood pressure is best managed by:","options":["Giving atropine immediately","Reducing/stopping the dexmedetomidine and reassessing, as the bradycardia is a reflex to high vascular tone","Giving a glycopyrrolate bolus to increase the heart rate","Administering a rapid fluid bolus to correct the bradycardia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Alpha-2 agonist bradycardia is a baroreflex response to drug-induced vasoconstriction/hypertension. Giving an anticholinergic into high afterload increases myocardial work and can cause dangerous hypertension; reduce/stop the alpha-2 first."},{"id":"ncx04","domain":"Complications","q":"To reduce the risk of regurgitation and aspiration during anesthesia, you should:","options":["Fast the patient for at least 24 hours to completely empty the stomach","Use appropriate fasting, keep the cuff inflated, and position the head to allow drainage","Place the patient in dorsal recumbency immediately after induction","Extubate while the patient is still deeply anesthetized"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aspiration prevention includes appropriate (not excessive) fasting, a properly inflated ET cuff, head-down positioning if regurgitation occurs, suctioning, and delaying extubation until protective airway reflexes return."},{"id":"ncx05","domain":"Complications","q":"When should the endotracheal tube cuff be deflated and the tube removed during recovery?","options":["As soon as the patient makes any voluntary limb movement","When the patient regains a swallowing reflex and protective airway control (except in at-risk patients)","Immediately after the surgical procedure ends","As soon as spontaneous breathing resumes"],"answer":1,"explain":"Extubate when swallowing returns and the patient can protect its airway. Brachycephalic and aspiration-risk patients are kept intubated as long as tolerated. Premature extubation risks obstruction or aspiration."},{"id":"ncx06","domain":"Complications","q":"Hypoventilation under anesthesia is best managed by:","options":["Increasing the fresh gas oxygen flow to wash out CO2","Providing assisted or controlled (manual or mechanical) ventilation","Giving doxapram as the first-line treatment","Increasing the inhalant to relax the patient"],"answer":1,"explain":"Anesthetic-induced hypoventilation (rising ETCO2) is treated by assisting or controlling ventilation to normalize CO2, while addressing depth and ensuring a patent airway and adequate oxygen flow."},{"id":"ncx07","domain":"Complications","q":"A sudden loss of the pulse oximeter signal and ETCO2 waveform together most urgently suggests:","options":["A monitor cable or battery malfunction only","Possible cardiac arrest, airway disconnection, or severe low-flow state — assess the patient immediately","A light plane of anesthesia","Motion artifact from surgical manipulation only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Simultaneous loss of SpO2 and ETCO2 signals demands immediate patient assessment — rule out cardiac arrest, airway disconnection/obstruction, esophageal intubation, or a severe low-perfusion state — rather than assuming equipment failure."},{"id":"ncx08","domain":"Complications","q":"Which is an appropriate intervention for intraoperative hypothermia?","options":["Placing electric heating pads directly against the skin","Forced warm air blankets, warmed IV fluids, and minimizing exposure","Rapidly infusing room-temperature crystalloid fluids","Increasing the oxygen flow rate to warm the airway"],"answer":1,"explain":"Active warming — forced warm air blankets, warmed fluids, insulating the patient, and limiting surface exposure/wet fur — counteracts hypothermia, which prolongs recovery and impairs coagulation and drug clearance."},{"id":"nvf01","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"Controlled mechanical ventilation is indicated when:","options":["Whenever end-tidal CO2 falls below 20 mmHg","Hypoventilation, apnea, open-chest surgery, or neuromuscular blockade is present","Only when SpO2 remains above 95% on room air","During recovery to speed elimination of inhalant anesthetics"],"answer":1,"explain":"IPPV/mechanical ventilation is used when spontaneous ventilation is inadequate — during apnea, significant hypoventilation, thoracotomy (open chest), or neuromuscular blockade — to maintain normal oxygenation and CO2."},{"id":"nvf02","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"Which crystalloid is considered a balanced, replacement isotonic fluid?","options":["D5W","0.45% NaCl","Lactated Ringer's solution (LRS)","3% hypertonic saline"],"answer":2,"explain":"LRS (and similar like Plasmalyte/Normosol) is a balanced isotonic replacement crystalloid with electrolyte composition near plasma and a buffer, suitable for routine intraoperative fluid therapy and replacing losses."},{"id":"nvf03","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"Hypertonic saline (e.g., 7.2%) is used in shock because it:","options":["Provides sustained, long-lasting intravascular volume expansion","Rapidly draws fluid into the vasculature for quick, small-volume resuscitation","Buffers metabolic acidosis through its lactate content","Acts as a synthetic colloid due to its large molecular size"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hypertonic saline osmotically pulls interstitial/intracellular water into the vasculature, giving rapid intravascular expansion with small volumes — useful in shock or head trauma — but the effect is transient and must be followed by crystalloids."},{"id":"nvf04","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"A risk of overzealous intraoperative fluid administration is:","options":["Increased blood viscosity that impairs tissue perfusion","Volume overload causing pulmonary edema, especially in cardiac or renal patients","Rebound dehydration as fluids rapidly redistribute to tissues","Severe hypernatremia and hyperchloremia in all patients"],"answer":1,"explain":"Excessive fluids can cause volume overload and pulmonary edema, particularly in patients with cardiac or renal disease. Modern guidelines favor conservative rates titrated to blood pressure and perfusion, reassessing frequently."},{"id":"nvf05","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"When manually ventilating ('bagging') an anesthetized patient, you should:","options":["Deliver rapid, shallow breaths at 40-60 per minute to maximize oxygenation","Deliver a smooth breath to a safe peak pressure (~10-15 cmH2O) at a normal rate, watching the manometer","Inflate to a peak pressure of 30-40 cmH2O to fully recruit the lungs each breath","Hold each breath for 5-10 seconds to improve gas exchange"],"answer":1,"explain":"Deliver gentle, smooth breaths to a normal tidal volume/peak pressure (~10-15 cmH2O in healthy lungs), at a physiologic rate, watching chest rise and the manometer — then reopen the pop-off valve to prevent barotrauma."},{"id":"nvf06","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"What is the main reason to monitor peak inspiratory pressure during positive-pressure ventilation?","options":["To calculate the patient's tidal volume directly","To avoid barotrauma/volutrauma from excessive airway pressure","To determine the correct fresh gas flow rate","To detect the depth of anesthesia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Monitoring peak inspiratory pressure prevents delivering excessive pressure that can cause barotrauma/volutrauma (pneumothorax, lung injury) and reduced venous return. Keep pressures in the safe range for the patient's lung condition."},{"id":"nap01","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"An ASA Physical Status I patient is best described as:","options":["A normal, healthy patient","A patient with mild systemic disease","A moribund patient","An emergency case"],"answer":0,"explain":"ASA I = a normal, healthy patient with no systemic disease (e.g., a healthy young dog for elective spay). The ASA scale (I-V, plus E for emergency) communicates anesthetic risk based on systemic health."},{"id":"nap02","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"Why is a thorough preanesthetic patient assessment (history, exam, bloodwork) performed?","options":["To determine the exact minimum alveolar concentration for that patient","To identify risk factors and tailor the anesthetic plan to the individual patient","To satisfy insurance and legal documentation requirements","To allow the technician to select the surgical approach"],"answer":1,"explain":"Preanesthetic evaluation identifies conditions (cardiac, renal, hepatic, hydration, age) that alter anesthetic risk and drug choices, allowing the plan to be customized and complications anticipated — central to safe, patient-specific anesthesia."},{"id":"nap03","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"The four stages of anesthesia describe progression from:","options":["Premedication, induction, maintenance, and recovery","Voluntary excitement through surgical anesthesia toward overdose","Sedation, unconsciousness, analgesia, then amnesia","Analgesia, surgical anesthesia, recovery, then extubation"],"answer":1,"explain":"The classic stages progress: Stage I (analgesia/disorientation), Stage II (involuntary excitement), Stage III (surgical anesthesia, divided into planes), and Stage IV (anesthetic overdose/medullary depression). Smooth induction minimizes Stage II."},{"id":"nap04","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"Stage II (the excitement stage) is best minimized by:","options":["Slow, gradual induction","Adequate premedication and rapid, smooth IV induction to pass through it quickly","Avoiding all premedication","Using inhalant induction by mask in all patients"],"answer":1,"explain":"Stage II features involuntary excitement and exaggerated reflexes. Good premedication plus a rapid, smooth IV induction moves the patient quickly through this stage, reducing the risk of excitement, injury, and arrhythmias."},{"id":"nap05","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"Which describes 'surgical anesthesia' (Stage III)?","options":["Early disorientation and analgesia with the patient still conscious","Unconsciousness with progressive loss of reflexes and muscle relaxation suitable for surgery","Involuntary excitement, breath-holding, and exaggerated reflexes","Medullary depression with cardiovascular and respiratory collapse"],"answer":1,"explain":"Stage III (surgical anesthesia) is unconsciousness with adequate muscle relaxation and analgesia for surgery, subdivided into planes by reflex/eye signs. The goal is a stable plane — deep enough for surgery, not so deep as to risk Stage IV."},{"id":"nap06","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"Eye position and reflexes are used to gauge anesthetic depth. In a surgical plane with most inhalants, the eye is typically:","options":["Central with a brisk palpebral reflex","Ventromedially rotated with a diminished palpebral reflex","Central and fixed with a dilated pupil and absent reflexes","Nystagmus with an active corneal reflex"],"answer":1,"explain":"In an adequate surgical plane (with inhalants), the eye usually rotates ventromedially and the palpebral reflex diminishes. A central eye with brisk reflexes suggests a light plane; a central, dry eye in deep planes warrants caution. (Note: ketamine keeps eyes central/open.)"},{"id":"nap07","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"The single most valuable 'monitor' during anesthesia is:","options":["A continuous multi-parameter ECG and blood pressure monitor","A trained, attentive anesthetist continuously observing the patient","A capnograph measuring end-tidal CO2","A pulse oximeter tracking oxygen saturation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Technology supports but never replaces a vigilant, trained anesthetist. Continuous hands-on observation and interpretation of the patient and monitors enables early detection and correction of problems — the foundation of anesthetic safety."},{"id":"fp01","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog premedicated with acepromazine becomes hypotensive after induction. Which property of acepromazine most directly explains this?","options":["Beta-2 agonism","Alpha-1 adrenergic blockade causing vasodilation","Muscarinic blockade","Histamine release"],"answer":1,"explain":"Acepromazine antagonizes peripheral alpha-1 receptors, producing vasodilation and a fall in systemic vascular resistance. Combined with anesthetic-induced depression this can cause clinically significant hypotension, so it is avoided in unstable patients."},{"id":"fp02","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which agent is most appropriate to provide rapid, titratable intraoperative analgesia via CRI during a painful visceral surgery?","options":["Butorphanol","Fentanyl","Buprenorphine","Maropitant"],"answer":1,"explain":"Fentanyl is a potent, short-acting pure mu-agonist ideal for a titratable analgesic CRI during painful procedures, with rapid onset/offset and minimal cardiovascular depression aside from vagally-mediated bradycardia."},{"id":"fp03","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A cat with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy needs sedation. Which premedication choice is generally LEAST appropriate?","options":["An opioid such as butorphanol","Ketamine, due to increased heart rate and myocardial oxygen demand","Midazolam","A low-dose opioid with careful monitoring"],"answer":1,"explain":"Ketamine increases heart rate, contractility, and myocardial oxygen demand and worsens dynamic outflow obstruction in HCM cats, so it is generally avoided. Opioid-based protocols with benzodiazepines are preferred in these patients."},{"id":"fp04","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Why is methadone often preferred over morphine for a painful procedure in a patient prone to vomiting?","options":["Methadone is a partial mu-agonist with a ceiling effect","Methadone causes less vomiting and adds NMDA antagonism","Methadone directly blocks the chemoreceptor trigger zone","Methadone has no effect on opioid receptors"],"answer":1,"explain":"Methadone tends to cause less nausea/vomiting than morphine and provides additional analgesia through NMDA-receptor antagonism, making it useful when both potent analgesia and reduced emesis are desirable."},{"id":"fp05","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A patient received midazolam and remains excessively sedated. Which reversal agent is appropriate?","options":["Naloxone","Atipamezole","Flumazenil","Neostigmine"],"answer":2,"explain":"Flumazenil is the specific benzodiazepine antagonist and reverses midazolam-induced sedation. Because its duration is short, re-sedation can occur if the benzodiazepine outlasts it."},{"id":"fp06","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"What is the main advantage of using a mu-agonist opioid as part of premedication?","options":["It provides reliable muscle relaxation","It provides analgesia and is MAC-sparing, reducing inhalant needs","It produces amnesia and hypnosis sufficient for surgery alone","It causes marked, sustained hypertension"],"answer":1,"explain":"Mu-agonist opioids contribute pre-emptive analgesia and reduce the required inhalant concentration (MAC-sparing), improving cardiovascular stability — a central reason they are included in balanced premedication."},{"id":"fp07","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which describes why alfaxalone is titrated slowly to effect during induction?","options":["It must be given as a slow 10-minute infusion to be effective","Rapid administration can cause apnea and excessive cardiovascular depression","Rapid injection causes the steroid to precipitate in the vein","It has a very narrow margin of safety, unlike propofol"],"answer":1,"explain":"Like propofol, alfaxalone can cause dose- and rate-dependent apnea and cardiovascular depression if given too quickly. Titrating slowly to effect reduces these risks while achieving a smooth induction."},{"id":"fp08","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A patient on a fentanyl CRI for many hours has a slower recovery than expected. The best explanation is:","options":["Fentanyl is renally cleared only","Accumulation increases its context-sensitive half-time with prolonged infusion","An active metabolite accumulates and prolongs the effect","Hepatic metabolism converts it to a long-acting form"],"answer":1,"explain":"Fentanyl accumulates in peripheral tissues during long infusions, lengthening its context-sensitive half-time so plasma levels fall more slowly when stopped — prolonging recovery compared with a brief infusion."},{"id":"fphy01","domain":"Physiology","q":"A patient's stroke volume falls but heart rate rises, keeping cardiac output stable. This illustrates which relationship?","options":["Cardiac output = heart rate × stroke volume","Mean arterial pressure = cardiac output × systemic vascular resistance","Stroke volume = end-diastolic volume − end-systolic volume","The Frank-Starling preload–stroke volume relationship"],"answer":0,"explain":"Cardiac output equals heart rate times stroke volume; a compensatory rise in heart rate can offset a fall in stroke volume to preserve output — though this has limits and increases myocardial oxygen demand."},{"id":"fphy02","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which best explains why severe anemia threatens tissue oxygenation even with a normal PaO2?","options":["PaO2 determines total oxygen content","Most oxygen is carried bound to hemoglobin, so less hemoglobin means less oxygen delivered","Plasma carries most of the oxygen","A normal oxygen saturation ensures adequate delivery regardless of hemoglobin"],"answer":1,"explain":"Because the great majority of oxygen is carried bound to hemoglobin, a reduced hemoglobin concentration lowers arterial oxygen content and delivery regardless of a normal dissolved-oxygen tension (PaO2)."},{"id":"fphy03","domain":"Physiology","q":"During controlled ventilation, blowing off too much CO2 (hyperventilation) produces:","options":["Respiratory acidosis","Respiratory alkalosis","Metabolic acidosis","Metabolic alkalosis"],"answer":1,"explain":"Excessive ventilation lowers PaCO2 (hypocapnia), raising blood pH and producing respiratory alkalosis. This can reduce cerebral blood flow and shift the oxyhemoglobin curve, so normocapnia is the usual target."},{"id":"fphy04","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which physiologic change explains why a hypothermic patient may bleed more during surgery?","options":["Cold-induced vasodilation increasing surgical-site blood flow","Impaired coagulation enzyme and platelet function at low temperature","Reduced blood viscosity at low temperatures","Suppression of anticoagulant proteins C and S"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hypothermia impairs the enzymatic clotting cascade and platelet function, contributing to a coagulopathy and increased surgical bleeding — one of several reasons to actively maintain normothermia."},{"id":"fphy05","domain":"Physiology","q":"What is the main reason the hypoxic drive matters in a patient with chronic CO2 retention?","options":["They rely on high CO2 to breathe","Their respiratory drive depends more on low oxygen, so aggressive oxygen can blunt ventilation","Their central chemoreceptors are hypersensitive to CO2","Supplemental oxygen has no effect on their ventilation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Chronic CO2 retainers become reliant on the peripheral (hypoxic) drive to breathe; supplying high oxygen can remove that stimulus and reduce ventilation, so oxygen is titrated carefully with ventilation monitoring."},{"id":"feq01","domain":"Equipment","q":"What is the purpose of performing a low-pressure leak test before each anesthetic?","options":["To calibrate the vaporizer output concentration","To confirm the breathing system holds pressure so gas/anesthetic delivery and ventilation are reliable","To verify the CO2 absorbent is fresh and active","To confirm adequate oxygen pressure in the cylinder"],"answer":1,"explain":"A leak test confirms the circuit is intact and will hold pressure, ensuring reliable gas and anesthetic delivery, effective ventilation, and minimal waste-gas pollution. A failed test must be resolved before use."},{"id":"feq02","domain":"Equipment","q":"For a 35 kg dog, which breathing system is most appropriate?","options":["A non-rebreathing (Bain) circuit","A rebreathing (circle) system","An Ayre's T-piece with high fresh gas flow","A Jackson-Rees modified T-piece"],"answer":1,"explain":"Larger patients (generally over ~7 kg) are best served by a rebreathing/circle system, which uses lower fresh gas flows, conserves heat and humidity, and handles the larger tidal volumes efficiently."},{"id":"feq03","domain":"Equipment","q":"A capnograph baseline that fails to return to zero indicates a problem most likely located in:","options":["Water condensation blocking the capnograph sampling line","The CO2 absorbent or a one-way valve (rebreathing of CO2)","A cracked or leaking ET tube cuff","An incorrectly calibrated pulse oximeter"],"answer":1,"explain":"An elevated (non-zero) inspired CO2 baseline indicates rebreathing of CO2, usually from exhausted soda lime or a malfunctioning unidirectional valve — both of which require correction to prevent hypercapnia."},{"id":"feq04","domain":"Equipment","q":"Why must the pop-off valve be reopened immediately after delivering a manual breath?","options":["To allow the reservoir bag to refill with fresh gas","To prevent pressure buildup that can cause barotrauma","To restore normal fresh gas flow through the flowmeter","To allow exhaled CO2 to reach the absorbent"],"answer":1,"explain":"Leaving the pop-off closed after a manual breath allows circuit and airway pressure to climb, risking barotrauma and reduced venous return. It must be reopened right away during spontaneous ventilation."},{"id":"fmon01","domain":"Monitoring","q":"During anesthesia, the pulse oximeter reads 88% on room air. This corresponds to roughly what PaO2 and what clinical state?","options":["~100 mmHg, within normal limits","~60 mmHg, borderline hypoxemia requiring intervention","~75 mmHg, mild desaturation, no action needed","~40 mmHg, severe but expected on room air"],"answer":1,"explain":"An SpO2 of ~88-90% corresponds to a PaO2 near 60 mmHg — the threshold of hypoxemia. This warrants checking the airway, oxygen delivery, and ventilation and supplementing oxygen."},{"id":"fmon02","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Which ECG change should prompt the most immediate concern during anesthesia?","options":["Respiratory sinus arrhythmia","Runs of wide, bizarre QRS complexes (ventricular tachycardia)","An occasional isolated atrial premature complex","First-degree AV block with a prolonged PR interval"],"answer":1,"explain":"Sustained runs of wide, bizarre QRS complexes indicate ventricular tachycardia, which can compromise output and degenerate into fibrillation. It requires prompt assessment and may need antiarrhythmic treatment (e.g., lidocaine in dogs)."},{"id":"fmon03","domain":"Monitoring","q":"What does a falling blood pressure trend combined with a rising heart rate most likely signal under anesthesia?","options":["A lightening anesthetic plane with stable perfusion","Developing hypotension/hypovolemia triggering a compensatory tachycardia","An expected response to intravenous fluid loading","Hypothermia slowing the metabolic rate"],"answer":1,"explain":"A downward blood pressure trend with compensatory tachycardia suggests developing hypotension or hypovolemia. The cause (anesthetic depth, blood loss, vasodilation) should be identified and corrected promptly."},{"id":"fpn01","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Which is the best example of applying multimodal analgesia for a fracture repair?","options":["A high-dose opioid infusion as the sole analgesic","An opioid premed, a regional nerve block, and an NSAID once the patient is stable","An NSAID alone given at induction regardless of blood pressure","Increasing the inhalant concentration to control pain intraoperatively"],"answer":1,"explain":"Multimodal analgesia combines agents at different points of the pain pathway: an opioid (central), a regional block (transmission), and an NSAID (peripheral inflammation) — improving analgesia while lowering individual drug doses."},{"id":"fpn02","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Why is reassessing and re-scoring pain after an analgesic intervention important?","options":["It provides data for the medical record but rarely changes treatment","It confirms whether the intervention worked and guides further treatment","It confirms the correct anesthetic depth was maintained","It is unnecessary once an appropriate analgesic dose has been calculated"],"answer":1,"explain":"Pain management is iterative: scoring before and after an intervention with a validated tool confirms efficacy and guides whether additional or alternative analgesia is needed — central to responsible analgesic practice."},{"id":"floc01","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Before injecting any local anesthetic block, aspiration is performed to:","options":["Confirm placement within the nerve for a more complete block","Detect intravascular needle placement and avoid systemic toxicity","Remove air bubbles that could weaken the block","Mix the anesthetic with tissue fluid for faster spread"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aspirating before injection checks the needle is not in a vessel; inadvertent intravascular injection of local anesthetic (especially bupivacaine) can cause severe systemic toxicity, so a negative aspirate is confirmed first."},{"id":"floc02","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Which block is appropriate to desensitize the maxillary dental arcade?","options":["Inferior alveolar (mandibular) block","Infraorbital or maxillary block","Mental nerve block","Auriculotemporal block"],"answer":1,"explain":"The infraorbital and maxillary blocks desensitize the upper (maxillary) dental arcade, while the inferior alveolar/mandibular block addresses the lower arcade. Femoral/sciatic blocks are for the pelvic limb."},{"id":"fer01","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"What chest compression depth does RECOVER recommend for most dogs and cats?","options":["One-quarter of the chest width","One-third to one-half the width of the chest","Two-thirds to three-quarters of the chest width","Only as deep as needed to feel a femoral pulse"],"answer":1,"explain":"RECOVER recommends compressing one-third to one-half of the chest width, at 100-120/min, allowing full recoil between compressions to maximize coronary and cerebral perfusion."},{"id":"fer02","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"During CPR, why is allowing full chest recoil between compressions important?","options":["It reduces the risk of fracturing the ribs","Full recoil allows the heart to refill, improving the next compression's output","It creates time to deliver a breath between compressions","It lowers the compression rate to a safer level"],"answer":1,"explain":"Full recoil lets the chest re-expand and the heart refill with blood, so the next compression ejects an adequate volume. Leaning on the chest (incomplete recoil) reduces venous return and compression effectiveness."},{"id":"fcalc01","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 15 kg dog needs cefazolin at 22 mg/kg. The concentration is 100 mg/mL. What volume is given?","options":["1.65 mL","3.3 mL","6.6 mL","0.33 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dose = 15 kg × 22 mg/kg = 330 mg. Volume = 330 ÷ 100 = 3.3 mL. Perioperative antibiotics are typically given ~30-60 minutes before incision and redosed during long procedures."},{"id":"fcalc02","domain":"Calculations","q":"A CRI requires 60 mg of lidocaine added to a 1-liter bag. What is the resulting concentration in mg/mL?","options":["0.06 mg/mL","0.6 mg/mL","6 mg/mL","60 mg/mL"],"answer":0,"explain":"60 mg ÷ 1000 mL = 0.06 mg/mL. Confirming the final bag concentration after adding drug prevents dosing errors when setting the infusion rate."},{"id":"fsp01","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"What recovery precaution is most important for a brachycephalic dog?","options":["Extubate the moment a swallowing reflex returns to prevent tube damage","Delay extubation until the patient strongly rejects the tube, monitoring for airway obstruction","Position in dorsal recumbency to keep the airway straight","Sedate heavily during recovery to keep the patient calm and still"],"answer":1,"explain":"Brachycephalic airways obstruct easily on recovery, so the endotracheal tube is left in place until the patient is alert enough to actively reject it, with close monitoring and oxygen available."},{"id":"fsp02","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Why should fasting be kept short in rabbits before anesthesia?","options":["Fasting rapidly causes dangerous hyperkalemia and cardiac arrest","They cannot vomit, and prolonged fasting risks GI stasis and hypoglycemia","An empty gut greatly increases their risk of gastric dilatation-volvulus","Withholding food causes hypercalcemia due to their unusual calcium metabolism"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rabbits cannot vomit, so prolonged fasting does little to reduce aspiration risk while causing dangerous GI stasis and hypoglycemia. Only brief fasting to clear the mouth is appropriate."},{"id":"fcx01","domain":"Complications","q":"The first step when an anesthetized patient becomes hypotensive on a high inhalant setting is usually to:","options":["Increase the intravenous fluid rate as the first step","Decrease the vaporizer setting, since inhalant overdose is a common cause","Give an ephedrine bolus before adjusting the vaporizer","Administer atropine to raise the heart rate"],"answer":1,"explain":"Inhalant anesthetics cause dose-dependent vasodilation and myocardial depression, making excessive depth a leading cause of intraoperative hypotension. Reducing the vaporizer is typically the first corrective step, followed by fluids/inotropes if needed."},{"id":"fcx02","domain":"Complications","q":"A patient under anesthesia shows a rapidly climbing temperature with rising ETCO2 and muscle rigidity. This presentation should raise concern for:","options":["Hypothermia causing shivering","A hypermetabolic crisis such as malignant hyperthermia","A light plane of anesthesia alone","An acute anaphylactic drug reaction"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rapidly rising temperature and ETCO2 with rigidity suggests a hypermetabolic crisis (e.g., malignant hyperthermia). Management includes stopping triggering agents, aggressive cooling, ventilatory support, and specific treatment (dantrolene)."},{"id":"fvf01","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"During a thoracotomy, why is positive-pressure ventilation required?","options":["Surgical retraction of the diaphragm paralyzes it, preventing any breathing","The open chest removes the negative intrapleural pressure needed for spontaneous breathing","Inhalant anesthetics completely abolish the respiratory drive during thoracic surgery","The lungs must be held fully inflated and motionless for the surgeon to operate"],"answer":1,"explain":"Opening the chest abolishes the negative intrapleural pressure that drives spontaneous breathing, collapsing the lungs. Controlled positive-pressure ventilation is required to maintain gas exchange during thoracic surgery."},{"id":"fvf02","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"Why do current guidelines favor more conservative anesthetic fluid rates than older recommendations?","options":["Because anesthetized patients no longer lose fluid through evaporation or urine","To reduce the risk of volume overload and pulmonary edema while maintaining perfusion","Because inhalant anesthetics cause the body to retain excess sodium and water","To prevent dilution of the anesthetic drugs in the bloodstream"],"answer":1,"explain":"Excessive fluids risk volume overload and pulmonary edema, especially in cardiac/renal patients. Modern guidance uses lower rates (often ~3-5 mL/kg/hr) titrated to blood pressure and perfusion rather than fixed high rates."},{"id":"fap01","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"What is the main purpose of a thorough preanesthetic physical exam and history?","options":["To establish the patient's exact minimum alveolar concentration in advance","To identify risks and tailor the anesthetic plan to the individual patient","To fulfill legal and insurance documentation requirements","To allow the surgeon to choose the surgical technique"],"answer":1,"explain":"Preanesthetic evaluation uncovers conditions that change anesthetic risk and drug selection, allowing an individualized plan and anticipation of complications — a cornerstone of safe anesthesia."},{"id":"fap02","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"An ASA II classification corresponds to a patient with:","options":["No disease (healthy)","Mild systemic disease that is well controlled","Severe life-threatening disease","A moribund state"],"answer":1,"explain":"ASA II denotes mild, well-controlled systemic disease (e.g., controlled early-stage disease or mild obesity). The scale communicates anesthetic risk and helps guide planning and monitoring intensity."}];
const EXAM_SETS = [["phr01","phr07","phr13","adv01","np02","np08","np14","np20","fp04","phy01","phy07","adv12","nphy06","nphy12","fphy04","eq01","adv08","neq05","neq11","mon01","adv06","nmon05","nmon11","pn01","npn01","npn07","loc01","nloc01","nloc07","er01","ner02","ner08","calc01","ncalc03","fcalc01","sp01","nsp04","cx01","ncx01","ncx07"],["phr02","phr08","phr14","adv02","np03","np09","np15","np21","fp05","phy02","phy08","nphy01","nphy07","nphy13","fphy05","eq02","adv09","neq06","neq12","mon02","adv07","nmon06","nmon12","pn02","npn02","npn08","loc02","nloc02","floc01","er02","ner03","ner09","calc02","ncalc04","fcalc02","sp02","nsp05","cx02","ncx02","ncx08"],["phr03","phr09","phr15","adv03","np04","np10","np16","np22","fp06","phy03","phy09","nphy02","nphy08","nphy14","eq03","neq01","neq07","feq01","mon03","nmon01","nmon07","fmon01","pn03","npn03","fpn01","loc03","nloc03","floc02","er03","ner04","fer01","calc03","ncalc05","sp03","nsp06","cx03","ncx03","fcx01","vf03","nvf04"],["phr04","phr10","phr16","adv04","np05","np11","np17","fp01","fp07","phy04","phy10","nphy03","nphy09","fphy01","eq04","neq02","neq08","feq02","mon04","nmon02","nmon08","fmon02","pn04","npn04","fpn02","loc04","nloc04","er04","ner05","fer02","calc04","ncalc06","nsp01","nsp07","cx04","ncx04","fcx02","vf04","nvf05","nap01"],["phr05","phr11","phr17","adv05","np06","np12","np18","fp02","fp08","phy05","adv10","nphy04","nphy10","fphy02","eq05","neq03","neq09","feq03","mon05","nmon03","nmon09","fmon03","adv13","npn05","loc05","nloc05","adv16","ner06","ncalc01","ncalc07","nsp02","fsp01","adv17","ncx05","adv22","nvf06","nap02","fap01","vf01","vf02"],["phr06","phr12","phr18","np01","np07","np13","np19","fp03","phy06","adv11","nphy05","nphy11","fphy03","eq06","neq04","neq10","feq04","mon06","nmon04","nmon10","adv14","npn06","adv15","nloc06","ner01","ner07","ncalc02","ncalc08","nsp03","fsp02","adv18","ncx06","nvf01","fvf01","nap03","fap02","adv19","adv20","adv21","nvf02"]];
const MOCK_POOL = [{"id":"mp01","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A patient with hepatic insufficiency is scheduled for anesthesia. Which induction agent's pharmacokinetics are LEAST dependent on hepatic metabolism for termination of effect?","options":["Propofol","Alfaxalone","Ketamine","Diazepam"],"answer":0,"explain":"Propofol's effect terminates primarily through rapid redistribution and high total-body (including extrahepatic) clearance, so a single dose is less dependent on hepatic metabolism than agents like diazepam or ketamine, which rely more on hepatic biotransformation."},{"id":"mp02","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Why does repeated or continuous dosing of thiopental produce a markedly prolonged recovery compared to a single bolus?","options":["It is renally excreted only","Saturation of peripheral fat stores slows redistribution, so the drug must be metabolized","It reverses spontaneously","It is not protein bound"],"answer":1,"explain":"Thiobarbiturate recovery from a single dose is by redistribution to muscle/fat. With repeated dosing those depots saturate, so termination then depends on slow hepatic metabolism — producing a cumulative, prolonged recovery (a reason sighthounds tolerate them poorly)."},{"id":"mp03","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which best explains why an opioid premedication reduces the dose of induction agent required?","options":["Opioids are inhalant anesthetics","Opioids provide sedation and analgesia, lowering anesthetic requirements (MAC-sparing/dose-sparing)","Opioids block the GABA receptor","Opioids increase hepatic metabolism of the inducer"],"answer":1,"explain":"Opioids contribute sedation and analgesia and are MAC-sparing, so less induction agent and less inhalant are needed to reach and maintain a surgical plane — a core principle of balanced anesthesia that improves cardiovascular stability."},{"id":"mp04","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog received dexmedetomidine and is now bradycardic and hypertensive. Atipamezole is chosen for reversal. Why is the IM route preferred over rapid IV?","options":["IM works faster","Rapid IV reversal can cause acute hypotension, tachycardia, and excitement","IM avoids analgesia loss","IV is ineffective"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rapidly antagonizing alpha-2 effects IV can cause abrupt vasodilation/hypotension, reflex tachycardia, and CNS excitement. IM atipamezole provides a smoother reversal, which is why it is the recommended route."},{"id":"mp05","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which drug's analgesic action depends substantially on hepatic conversion to an active metabolite that dogs produce poorly?","options":["Hydromorphone","Tramadol","Fentanyl","Methadone"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tramadol relies on conversion to its active O-desmethyl (M1) metabolite for opioid effect; dogs generate little M1, making its opioid analgesia unreliable in that species — a frequently tested pharmacogenetic point."},{"id":"mp06","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Acepromazine can lower the seizure threshold concern aside, what hematologic effect should be considered in a patient with anemia or planned blood donation?","options":["It increases hematocrit","It causes splenic sequestration of red cells, decreasing PCV","It has no hematologic effect","It stimulates erythropoiesis"],"answer":1,"explain":"Acepromazine causes splenic relaxation and sequestration of red blood cells, transiently lowering the measured PCV. This is relevant in anemic patients and is why it is generally avoided before blood donation."},{"id":"mp07","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"What is the rationale for combining a benzodiazepine with ketamine for induction rather than using ketamine alone?","options":["The benzodiazepine prolongs ketamine's metabolism","The benzodiazepine provides muscle relaxation and reduces ketamine-associated rigidity and rough recovery","Ketamine reverses the benzodiazepine","It avoids the need for oxygen"],"answer":1,"explain":"Ketamine alone causes muscle rigidity and can produce rough, excitatory recoveries. A benzodiazepine (midazolam/diazepam) adds central muscle relaxation and smooths induction and recovery — the basis of the common 'ketamine-diazepam' co-induction."},{"id":"mp08","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A CRI of an ultra-short-acting opioid is desired for an anephric/hepatically-impaired patient. Which is most appropriate?","options":["Morphine","Remifentanil","Methadone","Hydromorphone"],"answer":1,"explain":"Remifentanil is broken down by nonspecific plasma and tissue esterases independent of hepatic and renal function, with a near-constant context-sensitive half-time, making it ideal for titratable CRIs in organ-compromised patients."},{"id":"mp09","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Why must nitrous oxide be discontinued with oxygen supplementation at the end of anesthesia ('diffusion hypoxia')?","options":["N2O is toxic to the kidneys","N2O rapidly diffuses out of blood into alveoli, diluting alveolar oxygen","N2O causes seizures","N2O increases metabolism"],"answer":1,"explain":"When N2O is stopped, large volumes diffuse from blood back into the alveoli, transiently diluting alveolar O2 and CO2 (diffusion hypoxia). Supplementing 100% O2 for several minutes after discontinuation prevents resulting hypoxemia."},{"id":"mp10","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A patient on an MAOI or certain behavioral medications may be at risk if given which analgesic adjunct due to serotonergic effects?","options":["Hydromorphone","Tramadol","Ketamine","Lidocaine"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tramadol has serotonergic activity; combined with MAOIs, SSRIs, or other serotonergic drugs it raises the risk of serotonin syndrome. A medication history is important before adding serotonergic analgesics."},{"id":"mphy01","domain":"Physiology","q":"A patient's PaO2 on room air is 95 mmHg but drops to 55 mmHg under anesthesia on 100% oxygen. This large alveolar-arterial gradient most likely indicates:","options":["Normal physiology","Significant V/Q mismatch or shunt (e.g., atelectasis)","Hyperventilation","Hypothermia"],"answer":1,"explain":"On 100% O2 a healthy patient should have a very high PaO2 (often >400). A PaO2 of only 55 reveals a large A-a gradient from venous admixture — V/Q mismatch or right-to-left shunt such as atelectasis — impairing oxygenation."},{"id":"mphy02","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which compensatory response to metabolic acidosis would you expect in a patient with intact ventilatory control?","options":["Hypoventilation to retain CO2","Hyperventilation to blow off CO2 (respiratory compensation)","No change in ventilation","Increased bicarbonate production within minutes"],"answer":1,"explain":"Metabolic acidosis is compensated by increased ventilation (Kussmaul-type breathing) to lower PaCO2 and raise pH. Under anesthesia this compensation is blunted, so acidotic patients can decompensate quickly when ventilation is depressed."},{"id":"mphy03","domain":"Physiology","q":"During anesthesia, a patient's blood pressure is adequate but ETCO2 is rising steadily despite a patent airway and fresh absorbent. The most likely cause is:","options":["Hyperventilation","Anesthetic-induced hypoventilation (decreased respiratory drive)","Hypothermia","Excess oxygen flow"],"answer":1,"explain":"With a patent airway and good absorbent, a steadily rising ETCO2 reflects hypoventilation from anesthetic depression of respiratory drive/tidal volume. The remedy is assisted or controlled ventilation, and reassessing anesthetic depth."},{"id":"mphy04","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which statement about the relationship between hemoglobin and oxygen content is correct in an anemic patient with a normal SpO2?","options":["Oxygen content is normal because saturation is normal","Oxygen content can be dangerously low because there is less hemoglobin to carry oxygen","SpO2 measures total oxygen content","Anemia raises oxygen content"],"answer":1,"explain":"SpO2 reflects the percentage of available hemoglobin that is saturated, not total oxygen content. An anemic patient can have 99% SpO2 yet low oxygen-carrying capacity because there is simply less hemoglobin — a key distinction in oxygen delivery."},{"id":"mphy05","domain":"Physiology","q":"What effect does positive-pressure ventilation have on venous return and cardiac output in a hypovolemic patient?","options":["Increases venous return","Raises intrathoracic pressure, reducing venous return and potentially lowering cardiac output","No effect","Always improves cardiac output"],"answer":1,"explain":"Positive-pressure ventilation increases intrathoracic pressure, impeding venous return to the heart. In a hypovolemic patient with little reserve, this can significantly reduce preload and cardiac output, so volume status should be optimized."},{"id":"mphy06","domain":"Physiology","q":"Why does hypothermia prolong anesthetic recovery?","options":["It speeds hepatic metabolism","It slows drug metabolism and reduces MAC, so drugs linger and depth deepens at a given setting","It increases cardiac output","It raises body temperature set point"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hypothermia slows enzymatic drug metabolism and lowers MAC, meaning anesthetic agents persist longer and the patient is relatively more deeply anesthetized at any vaporizer setting — prolonging and roughening recovery. Active warming is important."},{"id":"mphy07","domain":"Physiology","q":"In a patient with increased intracranial pressure, why is hypercapnia particularly dangerous?","options":["It lowers cerebral blood flow","CO2-mediated cerebral vasodilation increases cerebral blood volume and raises ICP further","It causes hypothermia","It has no cerebral effect"],"answer":1,"explain":"CO2 is a potent cerebral vasodilator; hypercapnia increases cerebral blood volume and can dangerously elevate intracranial pressure. Careful ventilation to maintain normocapnia (or mild controlled hypocapnia) is critical in these patients."},{"id":"mphy08","domain":"Physiology","q":"What is the primary reason geriatric patients require lower anesthetic drug doses?","options":["Higher metabolic rate","Reduced organ reserve, lower MAC, altered body composition, and slower clearance","Increased muscle mass","Higher cardiac output"],"answer":1,"explain":"Geriatric patients have decreased hepatic/renal function, reduced cardiovascular and respiratory reserve, lower MAC, and altered body composition and protein binding — all of which reduce drug requirements and slow clearance, demanding conservative, titrated dosing."},{"id":"meq01","domain":"Equipment","q":"You select a non-rebreathing circuit for a 3 kg cat. Compared to a circle system, this requires:","options":["Lower fresh gas flows","Higher fresh gas flows to prevent rebreathing of CO2","No fresh gas at all","A CO2 absorbent canister"],"answer":1,"explain":"Non-rebreathing systems lack a CO2 absorber and rely on high fresh gas flows to flush exhaled CO2 from the circuit. They suit small patients (low resistance) but waste more gas and conserve less heat and humidity."},{"id":"meq02","domain":"Equipment","q":"During setup you notice the oxygen flush delivers gas that bypasses the vaporizer. Using the flush with the pop-off closed and patient connected risks:","options":["Light anesthesia only","Rapid pressure buildup and barotrauma","Improved oxygenation with no risk","Hypothermia"],"answer":1,"explain":"The flush delivers 35-75 L/min directly to the circuit, bypassing the vaporizer. With the pop-off closed and the patient connected, this rapidly builds dangerous pressure, risking barotrauma and cardiovascular collapse."},{"id":"meq03","domain":"Equipment","q":"A circle system's inspiratory unidirectional valve is stuck open. The clinical consequence is:","options":["Improved CO2 removal","Rebreathing of exhaled CO2 due to loss of one-way flow","Lower anesthetic delivery only","No effect"],"answer":1,"explain":"A malfunctioning one-way valve disrupts unidirectional flow, allowing exhaled (CO2-rich) gas to be rebreathed. This causes a rising inspired CO2 baseline on capnography and hypercapnia despite functional absorbent."},{"id":"meq04","domain":"Equipment","q":"Why should the vaporizer be filled with the correct agent only (e.g., isoflurane in an isoflurane vaporizer)?","options":["Color preference","Vaporizers are agent-specific and calibrated to that agent's vapor pressure; the wrong agent causes dangerous mis-delivery","All agents are interchangeable","To save money"],"answer":1,"explain":"Precision vaporizers are calibrated to a specific agent's saturated vapor pressure. Filling with the wrong agent delivers an unpredictable, potentially dangerous concentration (over- or under-dose), which is why agent-specific keyed fillers exist."},{"id":"meq05","domain":"Equipment","q":"The reservoir (rebreathing) bag size is generally chosen to be at least:","options":["Equal to tidal volume","About 6 times the patient's tidal volume (≈60 mL/kg) to allow for full breaths","Smaller than tidal volume","Irrelevant to patient size"],"answer":1,"explain":"The reservoir bag should accommodate a full inspiration plus reserve — commonly sized at roughly 6× tidal volume (~60 mL/kg). Too small a bag limits the patient's ability to take a full breath and impairs manual ventilation."},{"id":"meq06","domain":"Equipment","q":"A leak test reveals the circuit will not hold pressure even with the pop-off closed and the Y-piece occluded. The next best step is to:","options":["Use the machine anyway","Systematically check connections, bag, absorbent canister seal, and tubing to locate and fix the leak before use","Increase oxygen flow to compensate","Ignore it for short cases"],"answer":1,"explain":"A failed leak test must be resolved before use — a leak risks inadequate gas/anesthetic delivery, inability to ventilate, and waste gas pollution. Methodically check all connections, the bag, canister seals/gaskets, and hoses."},{"id":"meq07","domain":"Equipment","q":"Active scavenging systems should be checked to ensure they are neither obstructed nor applying excessive suction because:","options":["Obstruction wastes oxygen only","Obstruction can cause pressure buildup, while excess suction can collapse the reservoir bag and impair ventilation","They have no effect on the patient","They only matter after surgery"],"answer":1,"explain":"A blocked scavenger can transmit back-pressure to the circuit (barotrauma risk), while excessive active suction can evacuate the reservoir bag and apply negative pressure to the patient. Both compromise safe ventilation and must be verified."},{"id":"mmon01","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A capnograph shows a normal waveform that suddenly develops a 'shark-fin' (sloped) upstroke. This most suggests:","options":["Hyperventilation","Airway obstruction or bronchospasm (prolonged expiratory phase)","Esophageal intubation","Cardiac arrest"],"answer":1,"explain":"A sloping, shark-fin expiratory upstroke reflects uneven/obstructed alveolar emptying — seen with bronchospasm, a kinked or partially obstructed ET tube, or lower-airway disease. It prompts assessment of the airway and tube patency."},{"id":"mmon02","domain":"Monitoring","q":"During an anesthetic, the Doppler crystal over a pedal artery suddenly goes silent though the ECG shows a normal rhythm. The MOST appropriate immediate action is to:","options":["Assume the patient arrested and start CPR","Check the probe/patient for displacement or lost contact while assessing pulse, perfusion, and blood pressure","Turn off the Doppler","Deepen anesthesia"],"answer":1,"explain":"A normal ECG with lost Doppler sound is often a displaced probe or a perfusion problem (hypotension/vasoconstriction), not arrest. Verify probe contact and simultaneously assess pulse quality, mucous membranes, and blood pressure before escalating."},{"id":"mmon03","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Which finding best confirms correct endotracheal (not esophageal) intubation?","options":["A single normal SpO2 reading","A sustained, normal capnograph waveform over several breaths","Pink mucous membranes","Absence of coughing"],"answer":1,"explain":"A sustained, repeating normal capnograph waveform is the most reliable confirmation of tracheal placement, because the esophagus does not produce consistent CO2 waveforms. SpO2 can stay high transiently even with esophageal placement."},{"id":"mmon04","domain":"Monitoring","q":"An oscillometric blood pressure monitor repeatedly errors on a 2 kg cat. The best troubleshooting step is to:","options":["Increase anesthetic depth","Ensure correct (small) cuff size, proper placement, and minimize motion; consider Doppler instead","Stop monitoring blood pressure","Use a larger cuff"],"answer":1,"explain":"Oscillometric devices struggle in very small patients. Use a correctly sized cuff (~40% limb circumference), place it properly, minimize motion, and consider Doppler, which is often more reliable than oscillometric methods in tiny or hypotensive patients."},{"id":"mmon05","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A patient's ECG shows tall, tented T waves and a widening QRS during anesthesia of a blocked cat. The technician should immediately suspect:","options":["Hypocalcemia","Hyperkalemia","Hypothermia","Light anesthetic plane"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tall/tented T waves with QRS widening (and bradycardia) are classic ECG signs of hyperkalemia, common in urethral obstruction. This is a medical emergency requiring potassium-lowering therapy and cardioprotection (calcium gluconate)."},{"id":"mmon06","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Why is trending multiple monitored parameters over time more valuable than reacting to a single isolated value?","options":["Single values are always wrong","Trends reveal the direction the patient is heading and reduce the chance of acting on artifact","Trending requires no equipment","Single values are illegal to record"],"answer":1,"explain":"Anesthetic monitoring is about trajectory. A trend (e.g., steadily falling blood pressure or rising ETCO2) reveals a developing problem and distinguishes real change from a single artifactual reading, enabling earlier, more appropriate intervention."},{"id":"mmon07","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A pulse oximeter reads 100% on a patient breathing 100% oxygen, yet the patient is poorly perfused and pale. The reading should be interpreted as:","options":["Definitive proof of good oxygen delivery","Potentially misleading — oxygenation of hemoglobin can be adequate while oxygen DELIVERY (perfusion) is poor","Evidence of hyperventilation","A device error requiring no action"],"answer":1,"explain":"SpO2 reflects hemoglobin saturation, not delivery. A well-saturated but poorly perfused or anemic patient can still have inadequate tissue oxygen delivery. Saturation must be interpreted alongside perfusion (pulse, CRT, blood pressure) and hemoglobin."},{"id":"mpn01","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A dog under a stable surgical plane suddenly shows tachycardia and hypertension when the surgeon begins traction on the ovarian pedicle. The best interpretation and response is:","options":["The plane is too deep; lighten it","A nociceptive (pain) response; provide additional analgesia rather than only deepening inhalant","Equipment artifact; ignore it","Hypothermia; warm the patient"],"answer":1,"explain":"A sympathetic surge with noxious stimulation indicates inadequate antinociception. The appropriate response is to add analgesia (e.g., opioid bolus, local technique) rather than simply increasing inhalant, which would worsen cardiovascular depression."},{"id":"mpn02","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Which approach best reflects the principle of pre-emptive, multimodal analgesia for an orthopedic procedure?","options":["Give an NSAID only after recovery","Combine an opioid premed, a regional/local block before incision, and an NSAID when perfusion is normal","Use inhalant alone and treat pain only if the patient cries","Give a single postoperative opioid dose"],"answer":1,"explain":"Pre-emptive multimodal analgesia treats the pain pathway before and during injury at multiple sites: an opioid premed, a local/regional block placed before incision, and an NSAID once the patient is normotensive/normovolemic — reducing wind-up and total drug needs."},{"id":"mpn03","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Why might a constant rate infusion of an analgesic be chosen over intermittent boluses during a long, painful surgery?","options":["It eliminates monitoring","It maintains steady plasma levels, avoiding the breakthrough pain of trough periods between boluses","It is always less expensive","It avoids the need for a loading dose"],"answer":1,"explain":"A CRI maintains stable analgesic plasma concentrations, preventing the recurrent breakthrough pain (and sympathetic responses) that occur as intermittent boluses wear off. A loading dose typically precedes the infusion to reach effect quickly."},{"id":"mpn04","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A cat is hiding, hunched, and not grooming after surgery, with a high Feline Grimace Scale score. This indicates:","options":["Adequate analgesia","Likely ongoing pain requiring reassessment and additional analgesia","Normal postoperative behavior needing no action","Excessive analgesia"],"answer":1,"explain":"These behavioral signs plus an elevated validated grimace score indicate unrelieved pain. The appropriate response is reassessment and additional analgesia, then re-scoring to confirm the intervention worked."},{"id":"mloc01","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"While placing a mandibular nerve block you aspirate and obtain blood. The correct action is to:","options":["Inject anyway; the dose is small","Reposition the needle and re-aspirate until no blood is obtained before injecting","Switch to bupivacaine for safety","Inject half the dose intravascularly"],"answer":1,"explain":"A positive blood aspirate means the needle is intravascular; injecting risks systemic local anesthetic toxicity. Reposition and re-aspirate until negative before injecting. This is especially critical with cardiotoxic agents like bupivacaine."},{"id":"mloc02","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"For a thoracic limb amputation, which regional technique provides the most appropriate intraoperative and postoperative analgesia?","options":["Lumbosacral epidural","Brachial plexus block","Femoral and sciatic block","Intratesticular block"],"answer":1,"explain":"The thoracic (front) limb is innervated by the brachial plexus; a brachial plexus block provides regional analgesia for forelimb procedures including amputation. Epidurals and femoral/sciatic blocks target the pelvic limbs."},{"id":"mloc03","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"A patient receives a maximum-calculated lidocaine line block, and the surgeon asks for an additional bupivacaine block at another site. The technician should:","options":["Give the full bupivacaine dose; the drugs don't interact","Recognize that local anesthetic toxicity is additive and recalculate the combined total to stay within safe limits","Double the bupivacaine since lidocaine is weaker","Only worry about toxicity with IV injection"],"answer":1,"explain":"Local anesthetic toxicity from different agents is additive. The combined dose of all local anesthetics (and from all routes) must be totaled and kept below safe maximums to prevent systemic toxicity (LAST)."},{"id":"mloc04","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Epidural morphine is selected for postoperative analgesia after a pelvic-limb surgery. Which formulation requirement is essential?","options":["Any morphine formulation works","Preservative-free morphine must be used to avoid neurotoxicity","It must contain epinephrine","It must be diluted in dextrose"],"answer":1,"explain":"Neuraxial (epidural/intrathecal) administration requires preservative-free solutions because preservatives can be neurotoxic to spinal tissues. Preservative-free morphine provides prolonged segmental analgesia with minimal motor block."},{"id":"mer01","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Mid-surgery, a patient's ETCO2 abruptly falls to near zero, the Doppler goes silent, and no pulse is palpable. The FIRST priority is to:","options":["Draw up emergency drugs","Begin high-quality chest compressions and ensure ventilation while calling for help","Take a blood pressure reading","Lighten the anesthetic and wait"],"answer":1,"explain":"These findings indicate cardiopulmonary arrest. Per RECOVER, immediate high-quality chest compressions and ventilation (BLS) are the first priority — started without delay — while help is summoned and the anesthetic is turned off; drugs follow."},{"id":"mer02","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"During CPR the ECG shows ventricular fibrillation. The indicated intervention not used for asystole is:","options":["Epinephrine only","Electrical defibrillation","Atropine only","Stopping compressions to observe"],"answer":1,"explain":"Ventricular fibrillation (and pulseless VT) is a shockable rhythm treated with electrical defibrillation, which is not used for the non-shockable rhythms asystole and PEA (managed with CPR plus epinephrine ± atropine)."},{"id":"mer03","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Why does RECOVER emphasize minimizing interruptions to chest compressions?","options":["To finish faster","Interruptions cause coronary and cerebral perfusion pressure to fall rapidly, taking time to rebuild","Compressions damage the heart","To conserve drugs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Each interruption causes a rapid drop in coronary and cerebral perfusion pressure that takes many compressions to re-establish. Minimizing pauses (e.g., during rhythm checks/compressor changes) sustains perfusion and improves outcomes."},{"id":"mer04","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"A sudden rise in ETCO2 from 12 to 35 mmHg during effective CPR most likely indicates:","options":["Worsening arrest","Possible return of spontaneous circulation (ROSC)","Esophageal intubation","Hyperthermia"],"answer":1,"explain":"During CPR, ETCO2 tracks pulmonary blood flow. An abrupt, sustained rise toward normal often signals return of spontaneous circulation, prompting a pulse/rhythm check and transition to post-arrest care."},{"id":"mcalc01","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 12 kg dog needs propofol at 4 mg/kg IV for induction. Propofol is 10 mg/mL. What volume is required?","options":["2.4 mL","4.8 mL","9.6 mL","1.2 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dose = 12 kg × 4 mg/kg = 48 mg. Volume = 48 mg ÷ 10 mg/mL = 4.8 mL, titrated slowly to effect to avoid apnea from a rapid bolus."},{"id":"mcalc02","domain":"Calculations","q":"A ketamine CRI is ordered at 10 mcg/kg/min for a 20 kg dog. How many mg are delivered per hour?","options":["6 mg/hr","12 mg/hr","120 mg/hr","1.2 mg/hr"],"answer":1,"explain":"10 mcg/kg/min × 20 kg = 200 mcg/min. ×60 min = 12,000 mcg/hr = 12 mg/hr. Converting mcg/min to mg/hr (×60 ÷1000) is a common multi-step CRI calculation."},{"id":"mcalc03","domain":"Calculations","q":"You must give 0.04 mg/kg of atropine to a 5 kg cat. Atropine is 0.54 mg/mL. The volume is approximately:","options":["0.07 mL","0.2 mL","0.37 mL","0.74 mL"],"answer":2,"explain":"Dose = 5 kg × 0.04 mg/kg = 0.2 mg. Volume = 0.2 mg ÷ 0.54 mg/mL ≈ 0.37 mL. Small-patient anticholinergic doses require precise measurement."},{"id":"mcalc04","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 25 kg dog in shock is to receive a one-quarter crystalloid shock bolus. Using 80 mL/kg as one blood volume, one-quarter bolus equals:","options":["200 mL","500 mL","2000 mL","100 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Full shock dose = 25 kg × 80 mL/kg = 2000 mL. One-quarter = 500 mL, given over ~15 minutes with reassessment of perfusion before deciding on further boluses."},{"id":"mcalc05","domain":"Calculations","q":"To prepare a fentanyl CRI delivering 3 mcg/kg/hr to a 10 kg dog at a pump rate of 1 mL/hr, what concentration must the bag be?","options":["10 mcg/mL","30 mcg/mL","50 mcg/mL","3 mcg/mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dose = 3 mcg/kg/hr × 10 kg = 30 mcg/hr. To deliver that in 1 mL/hr, the bag must be 30 mcg/mL. Working backward from desired dose and pump rate to concentration is a key compounding skill."},{"id":"msp01","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A brachycephalic bulldog is recovering from anesthesia. The single most important recovery precaution is to:","options":["Extubate as early as possible","Keep the patient intubated as long as it tolerates the tube and monitor closely for airway obstruction","Place in dorsal recumbency","Withhold all oxygen"],"answer":1,"explain":"Brachycephalic airways obstruct easily on recovery. Delaying extubation until the patient is awake enough to actively reject the tube, with close observation and oxygen available, reduces the high risk of post-extubation airway obstruction."},{"id":"msp02","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Why is prolonged preoperative fasting avoided in rabbits and rodents?","options":["They aspirate easily","They cannot vomit, and fasting risks GI stasis and hypoglycemia without reducing aspiration risk","They need full stomachs for intubation","Fasting improves their recovery"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rabbits and rodents cannot vomit, so prolonged fasting does not meaningfully reduce aspiration risk but does cause dangerous gastrointestinal stasis and hypoglycemia. Only brief fasting to clear the oral cavity is appropriate."},{"id":"msp03","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"An obese cat is dosed for several anesthetic drugs. For many agents, dosing should be based on:","options":["Total body weight always","Lean (ideal) body weight for many lipophilic/dose-sensitive drugs to avoid overdose","Double the body weight","The heaviest estimate"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dosing obese patients on total body weight can overdose them for many drugs; lean/ideal body weight is used for many agents (with clinical judgment), because adipose tissue contributes little to the volume of distribution for the active effect."},{"id":"mcx01","domain":"Complications","q":"Twenty minutes into anesthesia, ETCO2 climbs steadily, temperature rises rapidly, and the patient is tachycardic with muscle rigidity. After confirming ventilation and absorbent are adequate, the priority is to:","options":["Increase the inhalant","Discontinue triggering agents, begin active cooling, support ventilation, and treat for a hypermetabolic crisis (e.g., malignant hyperthermia)","Decrease oxygen flow","Continue and observe"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rapidly rising ETCO2 and temperature with rigidity suggests a hypermetabolic crisis such as malignant hyperthermia. Management is to stop triggering agents (volatiles/succinylcholine), cool aggressively, support ventilation/oxygenation, and treat (dantrolene)."},{"id":"mcx02","domain":"Complications","q":"A patient becomes hypotensive (MAP 50 mmHg) on 2% isoflurane. After confirming an adequate plane, the most appropriate FIRST step is usually to:","options":["Increase isoflurane to 3%","Decrease the isoflurane and give a crystalloid bolus, reassessing before adding inotropes","Stop IV fluids","Induce hypothermia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Inhalant overdose is a leading cause of anesthetic hypotension. Reducing the vaporizer (the likely cause) and giving a fluid bolus is the appropriate first step; if hypotension persists, an inotrope such as dobutamine is considered."},{"id":"mcx03","domain":"Complications","q":"A patient regurgitates during anesthesia. Besides suctioning and keeping the cuff inflated, an important step to prevent esophageal stricture is to:","options":["Leave the acidic fluid in the esophagus","Lavage the esophagus with water and suction it, lowering the head to prevent aspiration","Immediately extubate","Increase the anesthetic depth"],"answer":1,"explain":"Retained acidic material can cause esophagitis and stricture. With the cuff inflated, suction the pharynx, lavage the esophagus with water and suction, and position the head downward to prevent aspiration while the airway is protected."},{"id":"mcx04","domain":"Complications","q":"During recovery, a non-brachycephalic dog is extubated and develops stridor and increased respiratory effort. The most appropriate immediate response is to:","options":["Ignore it; it will resolve","Assess and support the airway/oxygenation, consider re-intubation, and identify the cause (e.g., laryngeal swelling)","Administer an NSAID","Place in dorsal recumbency"],"answer":1,"explain":"Post-extubation stridor and increased effort signal upper-airway obstruction (e.g., laryngeal edema/spasm). The response is to support the airway and oxygenation, be prepared to re-intubate or provide oxygen, and address the underlying cause."},{"id":"mvf01","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"A patient undergoing a thoracotomy (open chest) requires which ventilation approach?","options":["Spontaneous ventilation is sufficient","Controlled positive-pressure ventilation, because the open chest abolishes the normal negative intrapleural pressure","No ventilation support","Only oxygen flow-by"],"answer":1,"explain":"Opening the chest eliminates the negative intrapleural pressure needed for spontaneous breathing, so the lungs collapse. Controlled positive-pressure ventilation (IPPV) is mandatory to maintain adequate gas exchange during thoracic surgery."},{"id":"mvf02","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"A cardiac patient needs intraoperative fluids. Compared with traditional rates, current guidance favors:","options":["Higher rates to ensure perfusion","More conservative rates titrated to blood pressure and perfusion to avoid volume overload","No fluids at all","Hypertonic saline as maintenance"],"answer":1,"explain":"Modern recommendations favor conservative crystalloid rates (often ~3-5 mL/kg/hr, lower in cats), titrated to blood pressure and perfusion, especially in cardiac patients where overzealous fluids risk volume overload and pulmonary edema."},{"id":"mvf03","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"When manually ventilating a healthy anesthetized dog, an appropriate peak inspiratory pressure target is:","options":["2-4 cmH2O","10-15 cmH2O (up to ~20)","30-40 cmH2O","50 cmH2O"],"answer":1,"explain":"For healthy lungs, deliver breaths to roughly 10-15 cmH2O peak pressure (occasionally up to 20), watching the manometer and chest excursion. Excessive pressure risks barotrauma and reduced venous return; reopen the pop-off afterward."},{"id":"map01","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"A patient is classified ASA IV. This communicates that the patient:","options":["Is healthy","Has mild systemic disease","Has severe systemic disease that is a constant threat to life","Is brain-dead"],"answer":2,"explain":"ASA IV indicates severe systemic disease that is a constant threat to life (e.g., severe decompensated heart failure). The classification guides anesthetic risk assessment and planning; 'E' is appended for emergencies."},{"id":"map02","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"Why is a structured anesthetic record (timed vitals, drugs, events) considered a standard of care?","options":["It is only for billing","It enables trend recognition, continuity, accountability, and early detection of deterioration","It is optional documentation","It replaces patient monitoring"],"answer":1,"explain":"A detailed, timed anesthetic record lets the team track trends, detect deterioration early, ensure continuity across personnel, and provide a medico-legal account. It supports—but does not replace—vigilant hands-on monitoring."},{"id":"map03","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"During induction a patient enters a brief excitement phase with paddling and exaggerated reflexes. This corresponds to which stage, and the best response is:","options":["Stage III; deepen rapidly with more drug boluses indiscriminately","Stage II; ensure adequate premed and move smoothly/rapidly through it to a surgical plane","Stage IV; begin CPR","Stage I; stop induction"],"answer":1,"explain":"Involuntary excitement is Stage II. Good premedication and a smooth, prompt induction minimize time spent here, reducing the risk of injury, arrhythmias, and aspiration as the patient transitions into a stable surgical plane (Stage III)."},{"id":"map04","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"A trained anesthetist notes the eye has rotated ventromedially with a diminished palpebral reflex under inhalant anesthesia. This most likely indicates:","options":["A light plane requiring more depth urgently","An adequate surgical plane for many inhalant anesthetics","Stage IV overdose","Recovery is imminent"],"answer":1,"explain":"With many inhalant anesthetics, a ventromedially rotated eye and diminished (but present) palpebral reflex indicate an adequate surgical plane. (Note dissociatives like ketamine keep eyes central/open, so signs are agent-dependent and interpreted in context.)"},{"id":"mc01","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which property makes alfaxalone suitable for IM administration in cats when needed?","options":["It is formulated in propylene glycol","It is solubilized in cyclodextrin, allowing relatively low-volume, non-irritating injection","It must be given only IV","It requires reconstitution with saline only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Alfaxalone is solubilized in a cyclodextrin carrier (not propylene glycol/cremophor), making it relatively non-irritating and usable IM in some species/situations, though IV titration to effect remains the standard route."},{"id":"mc02","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"What is the main hemodynamic reason etomidate is chosen for a patient with severe cardiac disease?","options":["It is the cheapest agent","It preserves cardiovascular stability with minimal effect on contractility and blood pressure","It is a potent analgesic","It reverses arrhythmias"],"answer":1,"explain":"Etomidate causes minimal cardiovascular depression, preserving contractility and blood pressure, which is why it is favored for severely cardiac-compromised patients—accepting its drawbacks of adrenocortical suppression and possible myoclonus/pain on injection."},{"id":"mc03","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Why is glycopyrrolate sometimes preferred over atropine in pregnant patients?","options":["It is longer acting","It does not readily cross the placenta or blood-brain barrier","It is an analgesic","It reverses opioids"],"answer":1,"explain":"Glycopyrrolate is a quaternary amine that does not appreciably cross the placenta or blood-brain barrier, making it useful when fetal/central anticholinergic effects are undesirable, though its onset is slower than atropine."},{"id":"mc04","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A patient is on chronic ACE-inhibitor therapy for heart disease. The relevant anesthetic concern is:","options":["Hypertension under anesthesia","An increased tendency toward hypotension that may be refractory to fluids alone","Resistance to all anesthetics","Hyperthermia"],"answer":1,"explain":"ACE inhibitors blunt the renin-angiotensin compensatory response, so these patients are prone to anesthetic hypotension that may not respond fully to fluids alone, sometimes requiring vasopressor/inotrope support."},{"id":"mc05","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which opioid effect is most concerning during recovery and requires monitoring?","options":["Mydriasis","Respiratory depression and sedation","Increased appetite","Diuresis"],"answer":1,"explain":"Opioid-induced respiratory depression and sedation can persist into recovery; patients should be monitored for adequate ventilation and arousability, with reversal (titrated naloxone) available if depression is significant."},{"id":"mc06","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"What distinguishes a partial agonist like buprenorphine from a full agonist like fentanyl at the mu receptor?","options":["Buprenorphine has no receptor affinity","Buprenorphine produces a sub-maximal (ceiling) effect despite high affinity","Buprenorphine is an antagonist only","Fentanyl has lower efficacy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Buprenorphine binds the mu receptor with high affinity but produces a ceiling (sub-maximal) effect, giving a long duration but limited maximal analgesia and resistance to reversal—different from full agonists like fentanyl that produce maximal receptor activation."},{"id":"mc07","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which is an advantage of using a reversible sedation protocol (e.g., dexmedetomidine) for a brief diagnostic procedure?","options":["It cannot be reversed","Reversal with atipamezole allows a rapid, controlled recovery","It guarantees no side effects","It provides surgical anesthesia alone"],"answer":1,"explain":"A reversible protocol lets you antagonize the sedative (atipamezole for dexmedetomidine) to shorten recovery after brief procedures—useful for outpatient or quick diagnostics, while respecting the cardiovascular effects of alpha-2 agonists."},{"id":"mc08","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"What is the consequence of administering an NSAID and a corticosteroid concurrently?","options":["Enhanced analgesia with no risk","Markedly increased risk of GI ulceration and should be avoided","Improved renal protection","Reversal of both drugs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Combining NSAIDs with corticosteroids greatly increases the risk of gastrointestinal ulceration and is contraindicated. A washout period is recommended when transitioning between these drug classes."},{"id":"mc09","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which factor would shift the oxyhemoglobin dissociation curve to the right during surgery?","options":["Hypothermia","Acidosis and increased CO2 at the tissue level","Alkalosis","Decreased 2,3-DPG"],"answer":1,"explain":"A right shift (decreased hemoglobin O2 affinity, enhanced tissue offloading) occurs with acidosis, hypercarbia, hyperthermia, and increased 2,3-DPG—the conditions present in metabolically active tissues (the Bohr effect)."},{"id":"mc10","domain":"Physiology","q":"The Frank-Starling mechanism explains that, within limits, increased preload leads to:","options":["Decreased stroke volume","Increased stroke volume due to greater myocardial stretch","No change in output","Bradycardia"],"answer":1,"explain":"By the Frank-Starling mechanism, greater end-diastolic stretch (preload) increases the force of contraction and thus stroke volume, up to a physiologic limit. This underlies the cardiovascular response to fluid loading."},{"id":"mc11","domain":"Physiology","q":"Why is functional residual capacity (FRC) important during apnea or induction?","options":["It is the volume exhaled forcefully","It is the oxygen reservoir that delays desaturation when the patient is not breathing","It measures dead space","It determines heart rate"],"answer":1,"explain":"FRC is the gas (and oxygen) remaining in the lungs at end-expiration; it acts as an oxygen reservoir during apnea. Preoxygenation enlarges this reservoir, delaying desaturation during the apnea of induction/intubation."},{"id":"mc12","domain":"Physiology","q":"What is the expected acid-base picture in a vomiting patient with pyloric outflow obstruction?","options":["Metabolic acidosis","Metabolic alkalosis (loss of gastric HCl)","Respiratory acidosis","Respiratory alkalosis"],"answer":1,"explain":"Loss of hydrochloric acid through vomiting of gastric contents (especially with outflow obstruction) produces a hypochloremic metabolic alkalosis, which has implications for fluid and electrolyte correction before anesthesia."},{"id":"mc13","domain":"Physiology","q":"During one-lung ventilation or significant atelectasis, hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction serves to:","options":["Increase blood flow to collapsed lung","Divert blood away from poorly ventilated lung regions to improve V/Q matching","Lower systemic blood pressure","Raise body temperature"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction redirects pulmonary blood flow away from poorly ventilated (hypoxic) lung regions toward better-ventilated areas, improving ventilation-perfusion matching and limiting shunt."},{"id":"mc14","domain":"Equipment","q":"What does soda lime that has become hard, brittle, and is no longer changing color indicate?","options":["It is fresh","It is exhausted and must be replaced to prevent CO2 rebreathing","It needs water added","It is functioning optimally"],"answer":1,"explain":"Exhausted absorbent becomes hard/brittle and stops changing color (and produces little heat). It can no longer absorb CO2, leading to rebreathing and hypercapnia, so it must be replaced."},{"id":"mc15","domain":"Equipment","q":"Which breathing system component most directly conserves the patient's heat and moisture?","options":["A non-rebreathing circuit with high flows","A rebreathing (circle) system, which recycles warmed, humidified exhaled gas","The oxygen flush valve","The scavenger"],"answer":1,"explain":"A rebreathing/circle system recycles exhaled gas (warmed and humidified by the patient) through the absorber, conserving heat and moisture better than high-flow non-rebreathing systems—relevant to thermoregulation in larger patients."},{"id":"mc16","domain":"Equipment","q":"Before each anesthetic, why is checking the endotracheal tube cuff for leaks essential?","options":["To warm the tube","A leaking cuff cannot seal the airway, risking aspiration and inadequate ventilation/gas leakage","It changes the tube color","It is not necessary"],"answer":1,"explain":"Pre-checking the cuff confirms it inflates and holds without leaking. A defective cuff fails to protect against aspiration and allows gas leakage around the tube, compromising ventilation and increasing waste gas exposure."},{"id":"mc17","domain":"Equipment","q":"A pop-off valve that is accidentally left closed during a circle-system anesthetic will first manifest as:","options":["A deflating reservoir bag","A progressively distending reservoir bag and rising circuit pressure","Lower anesthetic concentration","Improved scavenging"],"answer":1,"explain":"With the pop-off closed, exhaled gas cannot escape, so the reservoir bag overdistends and circuit (and airway) pressure rises—an early warning of impending barotrauma. The valve must be reopened immediately."},{"id":"mc18","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Which best describes the normal capnogram during steady-state anesthesia?","options":["A flat line at zero","A repeating waveform with a clear plateau returning to a zero baseline on inspiration","A continuously rising line","Random spikes"],"answer":1,"explain":"A normal capnogram shows a square-ish waveform: a sharp expiratory upstroke, an alveolar plateau (peak = ETCO2), and a return to a zero baseline during inspiration. Deviations (raised baseline, sloped plateau, loss of waveform) signal specific problems."},{"id":"mc19","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Hypothermia can cause pulse oximetry to read inaccurately mainly because:","options":["Cold improves signal","Peripheral vasoconstriction and poor perfusion reduce the pulsatile signal the device needs","It increases hemoglobin","It warms the probe"],"answer":1,"explain":"Pulse oximeters need pulsatile arterial flow. Hypothermia-induced peripheral vasoconstriction and low perfusion weaken that signal, causing dropout or inaccurate readings—one reason to monitor and prevent hypothermia."},{"id":"mc20","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A second-degree AV block on the ECG is characterized by:","options":["No P waves at all","Some P waves not followed by a QRS complex","Wide bizarre QRS with no P","A completely regular rhythm"],"answer":1,"explain":"Second-degree AV block features intermittent failure of atrial impulses to conduct to the ventricles—some P waves are not followed by a QRS. The cause (vagal tone, drugs, disease) should be identified; symptomatic blocks may need treatment."},{"id":"mc21","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Why should a blood pressure cuff width be approximately 40% of the limb circumference?","options":["For comfort only","An incorrectly sized cuff gives inaccurate readings (too narrow reads high, too wide reads low)","To match the monitor color","It does not matter"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cuff width affects accuracy: ~40% of limb circumference gives the most accurate readings. A too-narrow cuff overestimates and a too-wide cuff underestimates blood pressure—proper sizing is essential for meaningful values."},{"id":"mc22","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Which describes 'allodynia,' a feature of maladaptive pain?","options":["Pain from a normally non-painful stimulus (e.g., light touch)","Absence of all pain","Pain only with deep pressure","Improved healing"],"answer":0,"explain":"Allodynia is pain evoked by a stimulus that is not normally painful (such as light touch), reflecting central sensitization. Recognizing maladaptive pain features supports aggressive multimodal and pre-emptive analgesic strategies."},{"id":"mc23","domain":"Pain Management","q":"What is a key benefit of incorporating local/regional anesthesia into a balanced protocol?","options":["It eliminates the need for monitoring","It blocks nociceptive input at the source, reducing inhalant/opioid requirements and central sensitization","It causes deep sedation","It raises blood pressure"],"answer":1,"explain":"Local/regional techniques interrupt nociceptive transmission at or near its source, substantially reducing systemic anesthetic and analgesic requirements and limiting central sensitization—a cornerstone of balanced, multimodal analgesia."},{"id":"mc24","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Which sign during placement suggests a local anesthetic has been inadvertently given intravascularly?","options":["Improved analgesia","Early signs of systemic toxicity such as twitching or seizures shortly after injection","Local swelling only","Slower onset"],"answer":1,"explain":"Inadvertent intravascular injection produces rapid systemic local anesthetic toxicity—muscle twitching, tremors, and seizures, progressing to cardiovascular collapse with bupivacaine. Aspiration before injection and incremental dosing reduce this risk."},{"id":"mc25","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"For a declaw (onychectomy) in a cat, an appropriate regional technique is a:","options":["Epidural","Four-point or ring block of the distal limb/digits with local anesthetic","Brachial plexus block only for hind paws","Intratesticular block"],"answer":1,"explain":"Distal forelimb/digital blocks (e.g., a four-point or ring block) desensitize the paw for onychectomy, providing excellent multimodal analgesia and reducing anesthetic requirements—within safe local anesthetic dose limits for cats."},{"id":"mc26","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"What compression-to-ventilation approach does RECOVER recommend for an intubated patient during CPR?","options":["Pause compressions for each breath","Continuous chest compressions with simultaneous ventilation at ~10 breaths/min","Ventilate only, no compressions","30 compressions then 2 breaths with long pauses"],"answer":1,"explain":"In an intubated patient, RECOVER recommends continuous, uninterrupted chest compressions (100-120/min) with simultaneous ventilation at about 10 breaths/min, avoiding the pauses used in non-intubated basic life support."},{"id":"mc27","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Low-dose epinephrine is preferred over high-dose in early CPR because:","options":["High dose is cheaper","High-dose epinephrine can worsen post-arrest myocardial function and outcomes","Low dose has no effect","High dose is reversible"],"answer":1,"explain":"RECOVER recommends low-dose epinephrine (0.01 mg/kg) early in CPR; high doses can cause excessive vasoconstriction, increased myocardial oxygen demand, and worse post-resuscitation outcomes, reserved only for prolonged efforts."},{"id":"mc28","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 30 kg dog needs cefazolin at 22 mg/kg IV. The vial is 100 mg/mL. What volume is given?","options":["3.3 mL","6.6 mL","13.2 mL","0.66 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dose = 30 kg × 22 mg/kg = 660 mg. Volume = 660 mg ÷ 100 mg/mL = 6.6 mL. Perioperative antibiotics are often timed ~30-60 minutes before incision and redosed for long procedures."},{"id":"mc29","domain":"Calculations","q":"A maintenance fluid rate of 3 mL/kg/hr is ordered for a 40 kg dog. What is the hourly volume?","options":["80 mL/hr","120 mL/hr","160 mL/hr","40 mL/hr"],"answer":1,"explain":"40 kg × 3 mL/kg/hr = 120 mL/hr. Conservative intraoperative crystalloid rates are titrated to blood pressure and perfusion to avoid volume overload."},{"id":"mc30","domain":"Calculations","q":"You need to deliver 2 mg of hydromorphone. The concentration is 2 mg/mL. After drawing it up, you must dilute to 1 mL total for slow IV. How much diluent do you add?","options":["No diluent","0.5 mL diluent (1 mL drug + ... )","You add diluent to bring 1 mL of drug to a larger volume as needed; here 1 mL drug already equals the dose","2 mL diluent"],"answer":2,"explain":"2 mg ÷ 2 mg/mL = 1 mL of drug, which already equals the desired 1 mL volume, so no dilution is needed here. Recognizing when a dose already matches the target volume prevents dosing/dilution errors."},{"id":"mc31","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Why do birds require careful, continuous attention to ventilation under anesthesia?","options":["They have very large lungs in reserve","Their efficient air-sac system means restraint or positioning that limits sternal movement quickly causes hypoventilation","They cannot be intubated","They are resistant to inhalants"],"answer":1,"explain":"Birds depend on movement of the sternum/body wall to ventilate their air-sac system; positioning or restraint that limits keel movement rapidly impairs ventilation. Assisted/controlled ventilation is often needed during avian anesthesia."},{"id":"mc32","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A major reason equine recovery is high-risk is:","options":["Horses cannot be monitored","Their large body mass makes a coordinated, safe return to standing difficult, risking fractures and injury","They are immune to anesthetics","They never become hypotensive"],"answer":1,"explain":"Recovery is among the most dangerous phases of equine anesthesia: the horse's mass and flight instinct make standing hazardous, risking long-bone fractures, myopathy, and injury. Assisted/quiet recovery techniques aim to reduce this risk."},{"id":"mc33","domain":"Complications","q":"A patient under anesthesia has a sudden, sustained drop in ETCO2 with an otherwise unchanged ventilator. After confirming the airway, the next consideration is:","options":["Hyperthermia","A fall in cardiac output/pulmonary blood flow (e.g., hypotension, embolism, impending arrest)","Light plane","Excess analgesia"],"answer":1,"explain":"With unchanged ventilation, a sudden sustained ETCO2 drop reflects reduced pulmonary blood flow—from falling cardiac output, hypotension, pulmonary embolism, or impending arrest—prompting urgent assessment of circulation and perfusion."},{"id":"mc34","domain":"Complications","q":"What is the most appropriate way to prevent intraoperative hypothermia from the start of anesthesia?","options":["Wait until the patient is cold, then warm","Begin active warming early (forced warm air, warm fluids) and minimize heat loss throughout","Use cold prep solutions liberally","Increase the inhalant"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hypothermia is easier to prevent than to treat. Proactive measures—forced warm-air devices, warmed fluids, insulation, minimizing wet fur and exposure—begun early in the anesthetic maintain temperature and support smoother recovery and coagulation."},{"id":"mc35","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"Which patient most clearly requires controlled (rather than spontaneous) ventilation?","options":["A healthy patient under light sedation","An apneic patient receiving a neuromuscular blocking agent","A patient breathing normally on room air","A patient in recovery"],"answer":1,"explain":"A patient given a neuromuscular blocking agent is paralyzed and cannot breathe spontaneously, mandating controlled ventilation. Apnea, open-chest surgery, and significant hypoventilation are other clear indications for IPPV."},{"id":"mc36","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"A synthetic colloid such as hetastarch differs from a crystalloid in that it:","options":["Leaves the vasculature immediately","Contains large molecules that remain intravascular longer to expand plasma volume","Provides only free water","Cannot affect blood volume"],"answer":1,"explain":"Colloids contain large molecules that stay in the vasculature longer than crystalloids, expanding plasma volume more efficiently per mL—though concerns about coagulation and kidney effects mean crystalloids remain first-line, with colloids used selectively."},{"id":"mc37","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"What is the primary value of a preanesthetic 'time-out' or checklist before induction?","options":["It slows the team down unnecessarily","It systematically verifies patient, procedure, equipment, and plan, reducing preventable errors","It replaces monitoring","It is only for legal reasons"],"answer":1,"explain":"A preanesthetic checklist/time-out verifies patient identity, procedure, equipment readiness, drug doses, and the anesthetic plan, catching omissions before they cause harm—an evidence-based way to reduce preventable anesthetic errors."}];

